name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was modified by addition; either by changing the frequency, strength or amount. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was maintained. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was modified by subtraction, either by changing the frequency, strength or amount. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was modified by temporarily terminating a prescribed regimen of medication. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was modified through termination of a prescribed regimen of medication. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context. (NCI)

name: Action Taken with Study Treatment
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

name: Acute Coronary Syndrome Presentation Category
definition: A myocardial infarction that does not produce elevation in the ST segments of the ECG.
term: Non-ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: Acute Coronary Syndrome Presentation Category
definition: Different than the one(s) previously specified or mentioned. (NCI)

name: Acute Coronary Syndrome Presentation Category
definition: A myocardial infarction that produces elevation in the ST segments of the ECG.
term: ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: Acute Coronary Syndrome Presentation Category
definition: Angina pectoris which has not recently changed in frequency, duration or intensity. Stable angina pectoris is relieved by rest or administration of oral, sublingual or transdermal antianginal medications.

name: Acute Coronary Syndrome Presentation Category
definition: Angina pectoris (or equivalent type of ischemic discomfort) which has recently changed in frequency, duration, intensity, or occurs at rest.

name: Age Unit
definition: The time for Earth to make a complete rotation on its axis; ordinarily divided into twenty-four hours. This also refers to a specific day. (NCI)

name: Age Unit
definition: A unit measure of time equal to 3,600 seconds or 60 minutes. It is approximately 1/24 of a median day. (NCI)

name: Age Unit
definition: One of the 12 divisions of a year as determined by a calendar. It corresponds to the unit of time of approximately to one cycle of the moon's phases, about 30 days or 4 weeks. (NCI)

name: Age Unit
definition: Any period of seven consecutive days. (NCI)

name: Age Unit
definition: The period of time that it takes for Earth to make a complete revolution around the sun, approximately 365 days; a specific one year period. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The spinous process of the 5th lumbar vertebra.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the descending aorta that lies within the abdomen, beginning below the diaphragm and ending at its division into the right and left common iliac arteries. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the body that lies between the thorax and the pelvis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any lymph node within the abdomen.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the abdomen. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sixth cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An additional renal vessel originating from the aorta and entering the kidney at the proximal or distal end of the organ. Accessory renal arteries are found in 26-30% of humans.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Two cup shaped areas, one each on the lateral side of the lower pelvis that house the head of the femur to form the ball and socket joint of the hip. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tendon that connects the heel bone to the calf muscles at the back of the lower leg. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The junction of the upper distal end of the scapula to the distal edge of the collarbone, also known as the acromion and the clavicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper distal process of the scapula. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The arteries that arise at the junction of the proximal and mid-right coronary artery conduit segments.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Suprarenal gland. A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An almond-shaped group of basal nuclei anterior to the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle of the brain, within the temporal lobe. The amygdala is part of the limbic system. (MESH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A natural or surgically-induced connection between tubular structures in the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A rectangular socket or bony arch that connects the ends of the tibia and fibula to the talus.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery of the lower extremity that supplies blood to the anterior part of the leg and the foot.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach. This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The curved segment of the aorta between the ascending and the descending segments.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A valve that is located between and controls the flow of blood from the left ventricle of the heart and the aorta. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the blood vessels that includes the iliac artery and its origin from the aorta.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the aortopulmonary window.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The distal end of the appendix. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the skeleton that includes the bones of the upper and lower limbs, including the shoulder and pelvic girdles

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument covering the arm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A blood vessel that carries blood away from the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the skeleton that includes the skull and spinal column and sternum and ribs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The underside concavity where the arm and the shoulder are joined. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery that originates from the subclavian artery at the lateral margin of the first rib. It supplies the brachial artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of approximately 20-30 lymph nodes in chain formation that traverse the concavity of the underarm to the clavicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A large blood vessel which returns blood to the heart from the lateral thorax, axilla and upper limb. Each side of the body contains one axillary vein.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The dorsal area between the base of the neck and the sacrum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Clusters of neurons comprising the globus pallidus, putamen, caudate, nucleus accumbens, substantia nigra and subthalamic nucleus. They are involved with high level aspects of inhibitory motor activity in coordination with the excitation commands issued from the cerebellum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the moderately large superficial veins of the forearm that transports blood from the hand and the medial aspect of the forearm to the axillary vein. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A muscle in the upper limb. Its action involves the rotation of the limb and the flexion of the humeralradial joint.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A muscle in the back of the thigh. Its action involves the knee flexion and hip extension. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the ducts conveying bile between the liver and the intestine, including hepatic, cystic, and common bile duct.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The duct system that transports bile from its origination by hepatocytes in the liver to the small intestine. It is comprised of the common bile duct that connects the liver and gall bladder to the small intestine and the cystic duct that connects the gall bladder to the common bile duct. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue layers that form the urinary bladder. They include the mucosa, submucosa, smooth muscle, and serosa.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper, convex surface of the bladder. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the bladder that is formed by the posterior wall and is located opposite to the bladder opening. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The inferior portion of the urinary bladder which is formed as the walls of the bladder converge and become contiguous with the proximal urethra. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The triangular area in the bladder mucosa that is formed by the two ureteral orifices and the urethral orifice. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A liquid tissue with the primary function of transporting oxygen and carbon dioxide. It supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The entire physical structure of an organism. It is composed of anatomic systems, regions, cavities, and spaces. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The main section of the digestive tube that connects the esophagus to the small intestine. The body proper excludes the upper and lower sections of the fundus and pyloric portion respectively. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Calcified connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue occupying the spaces of bone. It consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells which give rise to the red cells, white cells, and megakaryocytes. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery originating at the axillary artery and branching into the radial and ulnar arteries. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An axillary lymph node along the brachial vein. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the brain that connects the cerebral hemispheres with the spinal cord. It consists of the mesencephalon, pons, and medulla oblongata. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The four connected cavities (hollow spaces) centrally located within the brain that connect posteriorly with the central canal of the spinal cord. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fifth of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sixth of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The seventh of the seven cervical vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A cerebral fissure that originates near the occipital lobe and terminates below the corpus callosum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A single-cusped (pointed) and usually single-rooted tooth located between the incisors and premolars. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest of eight carpal bones, located in the center of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of two arteries that supply oxygenated blood to the head and neck; the left common carotid branches from the aorta and the right common carotid from the innominate (brachiocephalic artery). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the small bones of the wrist joint, located between the radius and the ulna and the metacarpus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A saddle-shaped synovial joint between the metacarpal of the thumb and the trapezium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A plane joint primarily between the second metacarpal and the trapezoid, which also connects with the trapezium and capitate. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A plane joint between the third metacarpal and the capitate. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A plane joint between the fourth metacarpal and the hamate. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A plane joint between the fifth metacarpal and the pisiform. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An elongated gray mass of the neostriatum located adjacent to the lateral ventricle of the brain. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine. (OMD)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Celiac Axis Lymph Node; Celiac Lymph Node
definition: A lymph node at the base of the celiac artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of five superficial veins of the upper extremity, beginning at the radial aspect of the wrist area, wrapping around the forearm and emptying into the axillary vein. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the brain located at the base of the skull that is responsible for balance, equilibrium and movement. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers. It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other higher levels of mental function.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The left half of the cerebrum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The right half of the cerebrum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The layer located below the cerebral cortex that includes the forebrain, midbrain and hindbrain. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One half of the cerebrum, the part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the lymph nodes located in the neck. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any one of the seven vertebrae that start with C1, connecting the skull to the spine, and ends with C7, which joins the cervical with the thoracic spine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower part of the uterus occupying the region between the isthmus of the uterus and the vagina. It is divided into supravaginal and vaginal portions. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Part of the medial aspect of the cerebral cortex. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: CIRCUMFLEX ARTERY AV GROOVE CONTINUATION ARTERY
synonym: CIRC AV; CIRCUMFLEX ARTERY AV GROOVE CONTINUATION ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The segment of the left circumflex artery that is distal to the third marginal branch, located in the atrioventricular groove.
term: Circumflex Artery AV Groove Continuation Artery

name: Anatomical Location
value: CIRCUMFLEX, OBTUSE MARGINALS, LEFT POSTEROLETERAL AND LEFT POSTERIOR DESCENDING ARTERY BRANCHES
definition: The left circumflex coronary artery and all of its branches.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone linking the scapula and the sternum. The clavicle is part of the pectoral girdle.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The erectile tissue in the vulva. It is composed of the corpora cavernosa and the glans clitoris.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Four vertebral segments positioned at the base of the spine that are fused. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small bone located at the bottom of the spine. The coccyx is a result of 3-5 fused rudimentary vertebrae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first part of the colon (large intestine) that starts in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen and ends at the transverse colon in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth portion of the large intestine (colon) that communicates with the transverse colon in the left-upper quadrant of the abdomen and the rectum below. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the large intestine that includes the descending and sigmoid colon. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A portion of the large intestine that includes the descending colon, sigmoid colon and rectum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The proximal segment of the large intestine that is located in the right side of the abdominal cavity. It includes the cecum (with the attached appendix) and the ascending colon. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third division of the colon (large intestine). It communicates with the ascending colon in the upper right-hand quadrant of the abdomen and the descending colon in the upper left-hand quadrant. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the external iliac artery at the inguinal ligament which bifurcates forming the deep and superficial femoral arteries.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the abdominal aorta which then bifurcates forming the internal and external iliac arteries.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the common iliac artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A thin, transparent tissue divided into the palpebral conjunctiva (covering the inner side of the eye lid) and the bulbar conjunctiva (covering the eyeball). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A dome-shaped, transparent, avascular tissue covering the front of the eye. It is composed of five layers: squamous epithelium, Bowman's membrane, stroma, Descemet's membrane, and endothelium. Refraction of light contributing to eye's focusing ability is its characteristic function. It contains unmyelinated nerve endings which are responsible for the high sensitivity of the tissue. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A principal artery that originates in the aorta. It supplies blood to the muscular tissue of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Anterior Descending Coronary Artery; Left Anterior Descending Coronary Artery
definition: A left coronary artery branch that descends on the anterior portion of the heart through the anterior interventricular groove. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LM; Left Coronary Artery; Left Main Coronary Artery; Left Main Coronary Artery Segment
definition: A coronary artery that arises from the aorta and bifurcates into the left anterior descending artery and the left circumflex artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A coronary artery that originates above the right coronary cusp and supplies blood predominantly to the right side of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The coronary vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the coronary circulation.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A blood vessel in the heart which returns coronary blood to the right atrium.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A white matter structure within the cleft that separates the left and right cerebral hemispheres in the mammalian brain. It is composed of a wide, flat bundle of 200-250 million axonal projections. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A group of cells that remain of the Graafian follicle following ovulation. This structure is composed of endocrine tissue and produces progesterone. This is needed to prepare the uterine lining for implantation by the fertilized egg. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the brain consisting of the neostriatum and globus pallidus.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cartilage positioned between the anterior end of the rib and the sternum. Its elasticity allows the ribcage to expand while breathing. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first hyaline cartilaginous joint between the ribs and costal cartilage.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The seventh hyaline cartilaginous joint between the ribs and costal cartilage.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the 12 paired nerves that originate in the brain stem. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone on the lateral side of the tarsus between the calcaneus and the fourth and fifth metatarsal bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. It increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the left circumflex artery that is between the second and third obtuse marginal branches.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the second digit of the hand or foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 2 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the second digit of the foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 2 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 2 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the second digit of the hand connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 2 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the third digit of the hand or foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 3 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the third digit of the foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 3 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 3 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the third digit of the hand connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 3 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fourth digit of the hand or foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 4 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fourth digit of the foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 4 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 4 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fourth digit of the hand connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 4 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fifth digit of the hand or foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 5 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fifth digit of the foot connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 5 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: DISTAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 5 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fifth digit of the hand connecting the middle and distal phalanges. (NCI)
term: Distal Interphalangeal Joint 5 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that is distal to the third diagonal branch.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: DISTAL RIGHT CORONARY ARTERY CONDUIT SEGMENT; DRCA
definition: The section of the right coronary artery distal to the origin of the acute marginal artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brain nucleus located in the medulla oblongata. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery of the dorsal surface of the foot, originating from the anterior tibial artery of the lower leg. The following arterial branches originate from the dorsalis pedis artery: the arcuate artery of the foot and deep plantar artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Venous channels within the dura mater of the brain which receives both blood from blood vessels within the brain as well as cerebrospinal fluid then drains into the internal jugular vein. Unlike other blood vessels, dural venous sinuses lack valves and other vessel associated layers.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the ear located within the temporal bone that is involved in both hearing and balance and includes the semicircular canals, vestibule, and cochlea. (from American Heritage Dictionary online)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The external part of the ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A joint involving the humerus, radius and ulna bones.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue lining the chambers of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the cervix which is lined by single columnar epithelium (mucosa). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A space inside the uterus lined by a layer of mucus membranes called the endometrium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brain region in the medial temporal lobe near the hippocampus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The outer membranous connective tissue layer of the heart tissue. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone prominence to which ligaments and tendons of the joints are attached. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A crescent-like structure located in the upper and posterior surfaces of the testis. It consists of the efferent ductules and the duct of the epididymis. It facilitates the maturation of sperm that is produced in the testis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located above and adjacent to the elbow. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the digestive canal between the pharynx and stomach. It consists of three parts: the cervical part, from the cricoid cartilage to the thoracic inlet; thoracic part, from thoracic inlet to the diaphragm; and abdominal part, below the diaphragm to the cardiac opening of the stomach.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It corresponds to the inferior part of the lower third topographic segment of the esophagus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of skeletal muscle. It corresponds to the superior part of the upper third topographic segment of the esophagus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells predominantly of the smooth type. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The middle one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated and smooth types.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It includes the middle third topographic segment, as well as parts of the upper and lower thirds. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper one third of esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated type. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A light and spongy bone that is cubical in shape. This bone is positioned at the anterior part of the cranium, sitting between the two orbits, at the roof of the nose. It consists of four parts: a horizontal or cribriform plate; a perpendicular plate; and two lateral masses or labyrinths. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery in the lower torso. The external iliac artery becomes the femoral artery and is the main blood supply for the leg.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located along the external iliac artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the biliary tract outside the liver; the common hepatic duct joins the cystic duct to form the common bile duct. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The organ of sight or vision. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and that part of the crystalline lens which presents through the pupil. (Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed, p109) (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest space within the eye which is bounded by the lens and the retina and filled with the gelatinous vitreous humor. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Anyone of the short hairs that grow on the edge of the eyelid. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The anterior portion of the head extending from the forehead to the chin and ear to ear. The facial structures contain the eyes, nose and mouth, cheeks and jaws. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A synovial joint between two adjacent vertebrae. The facet joint links the articular process of one vertebra and the inferior articular process of the adjacent vertebra. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any bone that contributes to the facial structures, except those bones that are part of the braincase. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The 7th cranial nerve. The facial nerve has two parts, the larger motor root which may be called the facial nerve proper, and the smaller intermediate or sensory root. Together they provide efferent innervation to the muscles of facial expression and to the lacrimal and salivary glands, and convey afferent information for taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and for touch from the external ear. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A sheet or band of fibrous connective tissue enveloping, separating, or binding together muscles, organs and other soft structures of the body.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Female internal and external organs of reproduction.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sex organs of the female.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The rounded bony projection at the distal end of the femur.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The highest portion of the femoral bone that articulates with the acetabulum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the upper inner portion of the thigh. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The short, constricted portion of the thigh bone between the femur head and the trochanter. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A vein that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the blood vessels that includes the popliteal artery and its origin from the femoral artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper leg bone positioned between the pelvis and the knee. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cylindrical body of the femur. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The small, lateral calf bone extending from the knee to the ankle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The elongated bony body of the fibula.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the digits of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The nail at the end of a finger. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 1ST DIAG; FIRST DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The first artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 1ST LPL; FIRST LEFT POSTEROLATERAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the first branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 1ST OM; FIRST OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The first artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 1ST RPL; FIRST RIGHT POSTEROLATERAL ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the first branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area of the mouth under the ventral surface of the tongue.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The structure found below the ankle joint required for locomotion. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest and most medial toe of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second toe from the medial side of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The middle or third toe from the medial side of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth toe from the medial side of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The smallest and most lateral toe of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest part of the brain composed of the cerebral hemispheres, thalamus, hypothalamus, and the limbic system. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the face between the eyebrows and the normal hairline.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the brain located anterior to the parietal lobes at the front of each cerebral hemisphere. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The paired, mucosal lined air spaces located above the orbit and communicating with the nasal passages. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the stomach that lies above the cardiac notch. It allows for the accumulation of gases produced by chemical digestion. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A pear-shaped organ located under the liver that stores and concentrates bile secreted by the liver. From the gallbladder the bile is delivered through the bile ducts into the intestine thereby aiding the digestion of fat-containing foods. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A cluster of nervous tissue principally composed of neuronal cell bodies external to the central nervous system (CNS). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area around the esophagogastric mucosal junction where the esophageal mucosa transitions into the gastric mucosa. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The anatomical location where the esophagus joins to the stomach. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The system that includes the esophagus, stomach, small and large intestine, anus, liver, biliary tract, and pancreas. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper gastrointestinal (GI) tract is comprised of mouth, pharynx, esophagus and stomach while the lower GI tract consists of intestines and anus. The primary function of the GI tract is to ingest, digest, absorb and ultimately excrete food stuff. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower part of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the jejunum and ileum of the small intestine and the large intestine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper part of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The external sex organs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The soft tissue surrounding the neck of individual teeth as well as covering the alveolar bone. The tissue is fibrous and continuous with the periodontal ligament and mucosal covering. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The trough in the head of the scapula that receives the head of the humerus to form the shoulder joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A cluster of convoluted capillaries beginning at each nephric tubule in the kidney and held together by connective tissue.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The ninth cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The space in which the vocal cords are located. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The outermost and largest muscle of the buttocks. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A large, irregular, quadrilateral area of bone found at the neck of the femur. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lateral and inferior border of the stomach. Attached to it is the greater omentum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower segment of the hair that circles the dermal papilla and the hair matrix. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which the sebaceous glands open; the follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the hair that is enclosed within the hair follicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the hair that projects above the skin surface. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The medial bone in the distal row of carpal bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The thick and short hand digit which is next to the index finger in humans. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second finger from the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The middle or third finger from the radial side of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth finger from the radial side of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fifth and smallest finger from the radial side of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bony anterior part of the roof of the mouth separating the nose from the mouth. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The anterior and superior part of a human or animal bearing the mouth, the brain and sensory organs.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area of the body comprising the skull, facial bones and the cervical vertebrae, sinuses, orbits, salivary glands, oral cavity, oropharynx, larynx, thyroid, facial and neck musculature, soft tissue and lymph nodes draining these areas.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper rounded part of the humerus that fits into the glenoid cavity of the scapula. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A hollow muscular organ which receives the blood from the veins and propels it into the arteries. It is divided by a musculomembranous septum into two halves -- right or venous and left or arterial -- each of which consists of a receiving chamber (atrium) and an ejecting chamber (ventricle). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The most outer superficial part of the heart which is situated on the left 5th intercostal space. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The paired upper chambers of the heart. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the pulmonary vein and pumps blood into the left ventricle. The right atrium receives venous deoxygenated blood from the entire body via the superior and inferior vena cavae and pumps blood into the right ventricle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The superior portion of the heart located opposite to the apical portion. It is formed mainly by the left atrium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The left lower chamber of the heart that receives blood from the left atrium and pumps it through the aorta to the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower chamber of the heart located in the right side. It receives blood from the right atrium that is no longer oxygenated and it pumps it to the pulmonary artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue in the heart that separates the two atria (atrial septum) and the two ventricles (ventricular septum). (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower right and left chambers of the heart. The right pumps venous blood into the lungs and the left pumps oxygenated blood into the systemic arterial circulation. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue layers that form the cardiac ventricle. They include myocardium, endocardium, and pericardium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the celiac trunk that supplies the liver and branches to form the cystic, gastro-duodenalis and pyloric arteries.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the lymph nodes adjacent to the stomach and duodenum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Refers to the area associated with the hilum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the hilum of the lung within the mediastinum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lateral prominence of the pelvis from the waist to the thigh. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A curved gray matter structure of the temporal lobe lying on the floor of the lateral ventricle of the brain. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bone prominence at the distal end of the humerus to which ligaments and tendons of the joints are attached.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cylindrical, elongated bony body of the humerus.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A U-shaped bone supporting the tongue. This bone is located at the base of the tongue and is suspended from the tips of the styloid processes of the temporal bones by the stylohyoid ligaments. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The twelfth cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The final section of the small intestine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The most distal section of the ileum that is continuous with the cecum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A predominate bone structure which borders the ilium wing stretching from the anterior superior iliac spine to the posterior superior iliac spine.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The large smooth and concave surface of the ilium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the three lymph nodes of the pelvis: the superior gluteal, interior gluteal or sacral. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the teeth in front of the canines in either jaw designed for cutting or gnawing. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the three bones comprising the middle ear. This anvil-shaped bone is positioned between the malleus and the stapes. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the area below the clavicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the abdominal aorta that lies below the kidneys.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the brain below the tentorium cerebellum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A superficial or deep lymph node located in the inguinal area. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower region of the anterior abdominal wall located laterally to the pubic region. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A short thick blood vessel arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery with numerous branches that supply the organs, walls and viscera of the pelvis as well as the inner thigh.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located along the internal iliac artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The blood vessel that supplies the breast and the anterior chest wall with arterial blood. It is located in the chest wall. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the lymph nodes of the breast located under the ribcage, near the sternum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the first digit of the hand or foot connecting the proximal and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the first digit of the foot connecting the proximal and distal phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the second digit of the hand or foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the second digit of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the second digit of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the third digit of the hand or foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the third digit of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the third digit of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fourth digit of the hand or foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fourth digit of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fourth digit of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fifth digit of the hand or foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fifth digit of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint between the phalanges of the fifth digit of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bony region in the proximal portion of the femur between the greater, lesser and sub- (also called the third) trochanters.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The wall that separates the left and right ventricles of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract between the stomach and the anus. It includes the small intestine and large intestine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bile ducts that pass through and drain bile from the liver. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any lymph node within the thoracic cavity.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bony prominence of the lower part of the ischium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A tetrahedral region of adipose tissue located in the ischiorectal region with its base between the tuberosity of the ischium and the lower end of the rectum and its apex at the point where the obturator fascia and the Levator ani membrane divide.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The most posterior and ventral bone making up the pelvis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The connection point between two bones or skeletal elements. The joint may be fixed or movable. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Veins in the neck which drain the brain, face, and neck into the brachiocephalic or subclavian veins. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two bean-shaped organs located on each side of the spine in the retroperitoneum. The right kidney is located below the liver and the left kidney below the diaphragm. The kidneys filter and secret the metabolic products and minerals from the blood, thus maintaining the homeostasis. On the superior pole of each kidney there is an adrenal gland. Each kidney and adrenal gland is surrounded by fat. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The outer zone of the KIDNEY, beneath the capsule, consisting of KIDNEY GLOMERULUS; KIDNEY TUBULES, DISTAL; and KIDNEY TUBULES, PROXIMAL. (MSH2001)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The concave area of the kidney through which the renal artery enters and the renal vein and ureter exit the organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lobe of the kidney located in the lowest portion of the kidney. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The internal portion of the kidney, consisting of striated conical masses, the renal pyramids, whose bases are adjacent to the cortex and whose apices form prominent papillae projecting into the lumen of the minor calyces. (MSH2001)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lobe of the kidney located in the uppermost region of the kidney. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The space between the L2 and L3 vertebrae.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The space between the L3 and L4 vertebrae.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fifth lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A congenital anomaly of the spine, where an extra or supernumerary lumbar vertebra arises from below the 5th lumbar vertebra.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small rectangular thin plate forming part of the medial orbit wall. It is located posterior to the frontal process of the maxilla and articulates with the inferior nasal concha, ethmoid, frontal, and maxillary bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Paired, almond-shaped exocrine glands situated superior and posterior to each orbit of the eye that produce and secrete the watery serous component of tears. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LAD SEPTAL PERFORATOR ARTERY SEGMENTS; LAD SP
definition: The arteries that arise from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supply the interventricular septum.
term: Left Anterior Descending Septal Perforator Artery

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cartilaginous structure of the respiratory tract between the pharynx and the trachea. It contains elastic vocal cords required for sound production. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LAT 1ST DIAG; LATERAL FIRST DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the first diagonal artery.

name: Anatomical Location
value: LATERAL FIRST OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY
synonym: First Obtuse Marginal Lateral Branch; LAT 1ST OM; LATERAL FIRST OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the first obtuse marginal artery.
term: Lateral First Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LAT RAMUS; LATERAL RAMUS INTERMEDIUS ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the ramus intermedius artery.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LAT 2ND DIAG; LATERAL SECOND DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT

name: Anatomical Location
value: LATERAL SECOND OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY
synonym: LAT 2ND OM; LATERAL SECOND OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT; Second Obtuse Marginal Lateral Branch
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the second obtuse marginal artery.
term: Lateral Second Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LAT 3RD DIAG; LATERAL THIRD DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the third diagonal artery.

name: Anatomical Location
value: LATERAL THIRD OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY
synonym: LAT 3RD OM; LATERAL THIRD OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT; Third Obtuse Marginal Lateral Branch
definition: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the third obtuse marginal artery.
term: Lateral Third Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The opening of the left anterior descending coronary artery at its origin.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first posterolateral branch originating from the posterior atrioventricular left circumflex artery in left dominant and mixed circulations.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The opening of the left circumflex artery at its origin.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the left coronary artery that runs along the coronary groove.
term: Circumflex Branch of the Left Coronary Artery

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the distal end of the left main coronary artery that branches into the left anterior descending artery and the left circumflex artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the left main coronary artery that is bounded by its ostium and bifurcation.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The opening of the left coronary artery at its origin.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second posterolateral branch originating from the posterior atrioventricular left circumflex artery in left dominant and mixed circulations.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: LEFT POSTEROLATERAL DESCENDING ARTERY SEGMENT; LPDA
definition: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this branch arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation and supplies the inferior apex of the heart.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The outermost layer of cardiac tissue lining of the left ventricle.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two lower extremities in humans used for locomotion and support. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the leg. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Crystalline Lens; Lens; Lens Of Eye; Ocular Lens
definition: A biconvex transparent structure of the eye through which light is focused on the retina. The lens sits behind the iris and is supported by the zonule, which connects it to the ciliary body. The lens is an avascular structure. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A cone-shaped projection in the shaft of the femur in which the iliopsoas muscle is attached. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Band of fibrous tissue connecting bone to bone or cartilage to bone thereby supporting or strengthening a joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A body region referring to an upper or lower extremity. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The limb that is composed of the hip, thigh, leg and foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The region of the body that includes the arm, the forearm, and hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small tongue-like projection from the lower portion of the upper lobe of the left lung.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Fleshy fold which surrounds the opening of the mouth. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The external surface of the lower lip. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The external surface of the upper lip. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A triangular-shaped organ located under the diaphragm in the right hypochondrium. It is the largest internal organ of the body, weighting up to 2 kg. Metabolism and bile secretion are its main functions. It is composed of cells which have the ability to regenerate. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A groove on the surface of the liver.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lobe of the liver situated posteriorly located between the left lobe and the inferior vena cava.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The smaller lobe of the liver extending into the left side of the body.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An oblong shaped area of the liver that is situated inferior to the right lobe, bounded by the anterior margin of the liver and the porta hepatis.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The larger lobe of the liver extending into the right side of the body.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brainstem nucleus. It is the major brain site for the synthesis and secretion of norepinephrine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the respiratory system below the bifurcation of the trachea. It includes the lungs and the parts of the lungs such as the bronchi, bronchioles and alveoli.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area of the body below the ribs and above the hipbones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The vertebrae located below the thoracic and above the sacral vertebrae.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the vertebrae situated between the thoracic vertebrae and the sacrum in the lower part of the spine.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bone in the proximal row of carpal bones that lies between the scaphoid and triquetral bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The wedge-shaped area at the central portion of the lung through which the bronchi, vessels and nerves enter or exit the organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The 2-lobed lung located on the left side of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Lower Lobe of the Left Lung
definition: The larger lobe of the left lung, situated below and behind the oblique fissure. (NCI)
term: Lower Lobe of the Left Lung

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Upper Lobe of the Left Lung
definition: The smaller lobe of the left lung, situated above and in front the oblique fissure, which includes the apex. (NCI)
term: Upper Lobe of the Left Lung

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The 3-lobed lung located on the right side of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Lower Lobe of the Right Lung
definition: The lobe of the right lung situated below the oblique fissure. (NCI)
term: Lower Lobe of the Right Lung

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung
definition: The smallest lobe of the right lung, situated above the oblique fissure and below the horizontal fissure. (NCI)
term: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Upper Lobe of the Right Lung
definition: The lobe of the right lung, situated above the horizontal fissure, which includes the apex. (NCI)
term: Upper Lobe of the Right Lung

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found through out the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The concave side of the lymph node. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two main bronchi. It is narrower but longer than the right main bronchus and connects to the left lung. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two main bronchi. It is wider but shorter than the left main bronchus and connects to the right lung. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Male internal and external organs of reproduction.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sex organs of the male.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A hammer-shaped bone, part of three interconnected small bones located in the middle ear. It is attached to the inner surface of the tympanic membrane and its function is to transmit sound vibrations. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Lactiferous glands consisting of fibrous tissue connecting the lobes and fatty tissue in between the lobes.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Bone, Mandibular; Inferior Maxillary Bone; Lower Jaw; Mandible
definition: The lower jaw bone holding the lower teeth. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A honeycombed section of bone located near the base of the skull, protruding behind the outer ear. It is connected to the middle ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper jawbone in vertebrates: it is fused to the cranium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: MEDIAN OR LOWER CERVICAL LYMPH NODE
definition: A lymph node located in the median or lower region of the neck. (NCI)
term: Median Or Lower Cervical Lymph Node

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the mediastinum. Mediastinal lymph nodes are arranged in three groups, one on the lateral, another on the medial, and a third on the anterior aspect of the vessels; the third group is, however, sometimes absent. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A group of organs surrounded by loose connective tissue, separating the two pleural sacs, between the sternum anteriorly and the vertebral column posteriorly as well as from the thoracic inlet superiorly to the diaphragm inferiorly. The mediastinum contains the heart and pericardium, the bases of the great vessels, the trachea and bronchi, esophagus, thymus, lymph nodes, thoracic duct, phrenic and vagus nerves, and other structures and tissues. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area between the lungs; it contains the thymus, some lymph nodes, and vessels and branches of the internal thoracic artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The broadest part of the lower portion of the mediastinum. It contains the heart and the great vessels. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the lower portion of the mediastinum that is located behind the pericardium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the mediastinum that is located between the upper part of the sternum in the front and the upper thoracic vertebrae in the back. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower portion of the brainstem located between the pons and brainstem. This structure contains several descending and ascending tracts, lower cranial nerve nuclei, a significant proportion of the reticular system of the brainstem and other structures. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the intestines. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the mesentery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A double layer of peritoneum that attaches to the back wall of the abdominal cavity and supports the small intestines. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the five bones between the wrist and the fingers that form the skeleton of the palm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the first digit of the hand connecting the metacarpal to the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the second digit of the hand connecting the metacarpal to the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the third digit of the hand connecting the metacarpal to the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fourth digit of the hand connecting the metacarpal to the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fifth digit of the hand connecting the metacarpal to the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone belonging to the middle part of the foot located between toes and ankle. There are 5 metatarsal bones and they are numbered from the medial side. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A spheroid joint located between the heads of the metatarsal bone and the base of the proximal phalanx of the toe. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the first digit of the foot connecting metatarsal with the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the second digit of the foot connecting metatarsal with the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the third digit of the foot connecting metatarsal with the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fourth digit of the foot connecting metatarsal with the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fifth digit of the foot connecting metatarsal with the proximal phalanx.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the left circumflex artery between the first and second marginal branches.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery between the first and third diagonal branches.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: MID-RIGHT CORONARY ARTERY CONDUIT SEGMENT; MRCA; Mid-right Coronary Artery
definition: The section of the right coronary artery between the right ventricular artery and the acute marginal artery.

name: Anatomical Location
value: MID/DISTAL LEFT ANTERIOR DESCENDING CORONARY ARTERY AND ALL DIAGONAL CORONARY BRANCHES
definition: All of the arterial branches distal to the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery.
term: Mid-Distal Left Anterior Descending Coronary Artery and All Diagonal Coronary Branches

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The uppermost portion of the brainstem located between the pons and the diencephalon. The midbrain contains the cerebral peduncles, oculomotor, trochlear and red nuclei, substantia nigra and various other nuclei and tracts. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A dual-flap valve of the heart that regulates the flow of blood between the left atrium and the left ventricle of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brain region that is located in the dorsal part of the precentral gyrus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The moist, inner lining of some organs and body cavities (such as the nose, mouth, lungs, and stomach). Glands in the mucosa make mucus (a thick, slippery fluid).

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lining of the fleshy folds surrounding the mouth. It is comprised of the epithelium, basement membrane, lamina propria mucosae, and lamina muscularis mucosae. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A fibrous soft tissue with the ability to contract to produce force and motion.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The smooth muscle lining the uterus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of two small oblong bones placed side by side at the middle and upper part of the face. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The proximal portion of the respiratory passages on either side of the nasal septum lying between the floor of the cranium and the roof of the mouth and extending from the face to the pharynx. The nasal cavity is lined with ciliated mucosa, extending from the nares to the pharynx. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The thin wall between the two nasal cavities. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the pharynx in the back of the throat, at and above the soft palate. The nasopharynx is continuous with the nasal passages. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An oval-shaped bone of the tarsus found on the medial side of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The region that connects the head to the rest of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bundle of fibers that transmits electrochemical impulses encoding sensory and motor information from one body part to another.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The pigmented protuberance on the surface of the breast through which milk is drawn from the breast. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A structure of special sense serving as an organ of the sense of smell and as an entrance to the respiratory tract. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two channels of the nose, from the point where they divide to the external opening. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brain structure that is part of the septal nuclear complex. It is connected with the hippocampus, hypothalamus and amygdala.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The posterior part of the cerebral hemisphere. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the back of the head adjacent to the trapezius muscle.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The occipital region of the skin that covers the top of the head. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue that forms the tooth. It consists of the dental pulp, dentin, enamel, cementum, odontogenic epithelium, and periodontium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A prominence at the proximal end of the ulna. It forms the tip of the elbow. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Anatomical structure located in the vertebral forebrain that receives neural input regarding odors that have been detected by cells within the nasal cavity. The axons of olfactory receptor cells extend into the olfactory bulb. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the nasal mucosa composed of neuroepithelial tissue and mucus-producing Bowman's glands. The mucus moistens the epithelium and helps dissolve odor-containing gases. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the internal carotid artery that branches into two groups of vessels; the orbital group that supplies the orbit and surrounding parts and the ocular group that supplies the globe and muscles of the eye.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Optic Nerve Head; Optic Papilla; Second Cranial Nerve
definition: A portion of the retina at which the axons of the ganglion cells exit the eyeball to form the optic nerve. No light-sensitive photoreceptors are contained within this portion of the retina. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second cranial nerve. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cavity located at the upper end of the alimentary canal, behind the teeth and gums that is bounded on the outside by the lips, above by the hard and soft palates and below by the tongue. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Moist tissue lining the oral cavity, containing mucus secreting glands.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Eye Socket; Ocular Orbit; Orbit; Orbital Cavity
definition: The bony cavity of the skull which contains the eye, anterior portion of the optic nerve, ocular muscles and ocular adnexa. Seven bones contribute to the structure of the orbit: the frontal, maxillary, zygomatic, sphenoid, lacrimal, ethmoid, and palatine bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
