definition: The part of the pharynx between the soft palate and the upper portion of the epiglottis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the paired female reproductive glands containing the ova or germ cells; the ovary's stroma is a vascular connective tissue containing numbers of ovarian follicles enclosing the ova. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An irregularly shaped bone positioned at the back part of the nasal cavity between the maxilla and the pterygoid process of the sphenoid. It forms the posterior part of the hard palate and the lateral wall of the nasal fossa and helps to form the floor of the orbit as well as several adjoining parts. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The undersurface of the hand. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is the shape of a fish and about the size of a hand. It is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues. The endocrine pancreas makes insulin so that the body can use glucose (sugar) for energy. The exocrine pancreas makes enzymes that help the body digest food. Spread all over the pancreas are areas called the Islets of Langerhans. The cells in these areas each have a special purpose. The alpha cells make glucagon, which raises the level of glucose in the blood; the beta cells make insulin; the delta cells make somatostatin. There are also PP cells and D1 cells, about which little is known. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the pancreas from the point where it crosses the portal vein to the point where it enters the lienorenal ligament. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The pancreatic tissue that contains the islets of Langerhans. It is responsible for the production and secretions of the pancreatic hormones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An enzyme producing region of the pancreatic tissue containing the pancreatic acini and exocrine intralobular ducts which collectively secrete the digestive enzymes into the main pancreatic duct to drain into the duodenal part of the small intestine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: That portion of the pancreas lying in the concavity of the duodenum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The left extremity of the pancreas within the lienorenal ligament. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the lumbar region of the spine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the lumbar region of the spine, along the right lateral aspect of the inferior vena cava. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The subserous connective tissue of the pelvic floor of the supracervical portion of the uterus. The parametrium extends laterally between the layers of the broad ligament. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Accessory Sinuses; Nasal Cavity; Nasal Sinuses; Paranasal Sinus
definition: An air-filled cavity adjacent to the nasal cavity lined by a mucous membrane and located in the bones of the skull. There are four paranasal sinuses on each side of the face: ethmoid, frontal, maxillary, and sphenoid sinus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A usually small autonomic ganglion of the parasympathetic nervous system. The majority are located near or in the organs that they innervate. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of two small paired endocrine glands, superior and inferior, usually found embedded in the connective tissue capsule on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland; these glands secrete parathyroid hormone that regulates the metabolism of calcium and phosphorus. The parenchyma is composed of chief and oxyphilic cells arranged in anastomosing cords. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the trachea within the mediastinum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A cluster of neuronal cell bodies and their dendrites located just ventral and lateral to the spinal cord that give rise to the sympathetic nervous system.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the lobes of the cerebral hemisphere located superiorly to the occipital lobe and posteriorly to the frontal lobe. Cognition and visuospatial processing are its main function. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest of the three paired salivary glands, located in front of the ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located close to, on, or within the parotid gland. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A part of the substantia nigra. The pars compacta nerve cells contain melanin and are involved in motor control. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small flat triangular bone in front of the knee that articulates with the femur and protects the knee joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The caudal portion of the trunk, bounded anteriorly and laterally by the two hip bones incorporating the socket portion of the hip joint for each leg. Posteriorly it is bounded by the sacrum and coccyx. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any lymph node within the pelvic region. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bony, basin-shaped structure formed by the hipbones and the base of the backbone supporting the lower limbs in humans. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The male organ of urination and copulation. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin area around the anus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The potential body space formed between the parietal and visceral layers of the pericardial sac. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located anterior to the pericardium, posterior to the xiphoid process, and in the right and left cardiophrenic fat. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A conical membranous sac filled with serous fluid in which the heart as well as the roots of the aorta and other large blood vessels are contained. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the area around the hilum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area located between the anus and vulva in females, and anus and scrotum in males. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node of the pancreas. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any nerve outside the brain or spinal cord that connects with peripheral receptors or effectors. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The lower part of the abdomen that contains the intestines (the last part of the digestive tract), the stomach, and the liver. It is bound by thin membranes. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the abdominal cavity, intestine, and mesentery. It consists of the parietal peritoneum that covers the inside of the abdominal wall and the visceral peritoneum that covers the surface of the intestine and mesentery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue surrounding the urethra.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the posterior tibial artery that supplies the muscles on the lateral side of the lower leg.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A fold of lymphatic tissue covered by ciliated epithelium at the very back of the nose, in the roof of the nasopharynx. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A hollow tube that starts posterior to the mouth and nasal cavity and ends superior to the trachea and esophagus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A small endocrine gland within the diencephalon of the brain, situated beneath the back part of the corpus callosum, that secretes melatonin.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The medial bone of the proximal row of carpal bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Pea-sized endocrine gland located at the base of the brain in the pituitary fossa. It produces and secretes hormones such as oxytocin and vasopressin, to regulate the activities of the hypothalamus. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cavity lined by the pleura, located in the thorax and contains heart and lungs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The middle portion of the brainstem located between the midbrain and the medulla oblongata.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the popliteal artery that is located above the knee.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The segment of the popliteal artery that is located below the knee.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Lymph node located within the fat layer of the knee joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the transverse fissure of the liver. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the space between the portal vein and inferior vena cava, along the hepatoduodenal ligament. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Lymph nodes surrounding the portal vein. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A short thick trunk vein that transports blood containing the absorbed products of digestion from the intestine directly to the liver. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the posterior region of the neck. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: PDSP; POSTERIOR DESCENDING SEPTAL PERFORATORS ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The arteries arising from the right posterior descending artery that supply the interventricular septum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A terminal branch of the popliteal artery that runs along the tibia from the lower portion of the popliteus muscle to the lower ankle with numerous branches supplying the lower leg and foot.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, the arterial branch that arises from the distal right coronary artery in the posterior atrioventricular groove after the origin of the right posterior descending artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located anterior to the auricle of the ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The posteromedial region of the parietal lobe bounded by the marginal branch of the cingulate sulcus anteriorly, by the medial portion of the parieto-occipital fissure posteriorly and by the subparietal sulcus inferiorly.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Exocrine glands located at the anterior aspect of the genitals of some mammals, such as mice and rats, that produce and secrete pheromones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A brain region in the occipital cortex that receives visual stimuli from the retina. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the common femoral artery just below the inguinal ligament running close to the femur and ending in the lower third of the thigh with branches supplying the thigh muscles.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The walnut shaped accessory sex gland of the male reproductive system. It is located in the pelvis just below the bladder, surrounding the prostatic part of the urethra. The prostate gland secretes a fluid which is part of the semen. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The prostate gland lobe that is located on the lateral side of the organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper, smaller part of the prostate between the ejaculatory ducts and the urethra. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The prostate gland lobe that is located on the posterior side of the organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The section of the left circumflex coronary artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and extends to the first marginal branch.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the second digit of the hand or foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 2 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the second digit of the foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 2 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 2 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the second digit of the hand connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 2 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the third digit of the hand or foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 3 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the third digit of the foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 3 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 3 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the third digit of the hand connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 3 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fourth digit of the hand or foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 4 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fourth digit of the foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 4 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 4 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fourth digit of the hand connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 4 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A condyloid synovial joint within the fifth digit of the hand or foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 5 OF THE FOOT
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fifth digit of the foot connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 5 of the Foot

name: Anatomical Location
value: PROXIMAL INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 5 OF THE HAND
definition: A ginglymoid (hinge) synovial joint within the fifth digit of the hand connecting the proximal and middle phalanges. (NCI)
term: Proximal Interphalangeal Joint 5 of the Hand

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The section of the left anterior descending coronary artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and extends to the first diagonal branch.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: PRCA; PROXIMAL RIGHT CORONARY ARTERY CONDUIT SEGMENT
definition: The section of the right coronary artery proximal to the origin of the right ventricular artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Either of the two bones (left and right) that form the front of the pelvis. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A valve that is located between and controls the flow of blood from the right ventricle of the heart and the pulmonary artery. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest and most lateral of the basal ganglia lying between the lateral medullary lamina of the globus pallidus and the external capsule. It is part of the neostriatum and forms part of the lentiform nucleus along with the globus pallidus. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The muscular structure at the distal portion of the stomach, opening into the duodenum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A group of four powerful muscles in the front of the thigh. Their actions involve the extension of the knee joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The branch of the brachial artery that passes down the forearm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The long bone that extends from the lateral aspect of the elbow to the medial side of the carpus.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The slightly curved, prismoid, elongated bony body of the radius.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: RAMUS; RAMUS ARTERY; RAMUS INTERMEDIUS ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: An artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and is positioned between the left anterior descending coronary artery and the circumflex artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A group of nuclei that are located in the midline of the brainstem and release serotonin. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area where the sigmoid colon joins the rectum.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The terminal portion of the gastrointestinal tract, extending from the rectosigmoid junction to the anal canal. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the four quadriceps muscles, located in the middle of the front of the thigh. Its actions involve the extension of the knee joint and flexion of the hip. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node that drains lymph from a region of interest. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Either of two arteries (right or left) that arise from the aorta to supply the kidneys.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The funnel-shaped proximal portion of the ureter located within the kidney into which urine is secreted, from the collecting duct system of the kidney. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The organs and anatomic structures involved in inspiration and expiration of air and the exchange of carbon dioxide and oxygen.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A light-sensitive membrane that lines the back wall of the eyeball. The retina is continuous with the optic nerve and this way transmits optical images to the brain. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the ophthalmic artery that supplies the retina.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A retina layer that contains the axons of ganglion cells. It collects the visual impulses. (NCI)
term: Layer of the Ophthalmic Nerve Fibers

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located within the most inferior portion of the posterior mediastinum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the retroperitoneal space. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The back of the abdomen where the kidneys lie and the great blood vessels run. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any one of the paired bones, 12 on either side, extending from the thoracic vertebrae toward the median line on the ventral aspect of the trunk. The long curved bones which form the rib cage. Generally, ribs 1 to 7 are connected to the sternum by their costal cartilages and are called true ribs, whereas ribs 8 to 12 are termed false ribs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tenth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eleventh rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The twelfth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fifth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sixth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The seventh rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eighth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The ninth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The innermost layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue that lines the right atrium.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The opening of the right coronary artery at its origin.

name: Anatomical Location
value: RIGHT CORONARY ARTERY, RIGHT POSTERIOR DESCENDING, RIGHT POSTERIOLATERAL AND ACUTE MARGINAL BRANCHES
definition: The right coronary artery and all of its branches.
term: Right Coronary Artery and its Branches

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: RIGHT POSTERIOR ATRIOVENTRICULAR ARTERY SEGMENT; RPAV
definition: The arterial branch between the right posterior descending artery segment and the first right posterolateral segment.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: RIGHT POSTERIOR DESCENDING ARTERY SEGMENT; RPDA
definition: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, the arterial branch that arises from the distal right coronary artery between the acute marginal artery and the first right posterolateral segment. It supplies the inferior apex of the heart.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The branch of the right coronary artery that supplies blood to the right ventricular wall.
term: Right Ventricular Branch of Right Coronary Artery

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The innermost layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue that lines the right ventricle.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The prominence on the lateral surface of the sacrum, posterior to the auricular surface of the sacrum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the vertebrae forming the triangular bone just below the lumbar vertebrae.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The joint located between the sacrum and the ilium. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The triangular bone, made up of 5 fused bones of the spine, located in the lower area of the spine between the fifth lumbar vertebra and the coccyx. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An exocrine gland that secretes saliva. Salivary glands are mostly located in and around the oral cavity.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of two (Greater, Small) superficial veins of the leg and thigh. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin which covers the top of the head and which is usually covered by hair. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A nut-shaped bone of the wrist located in the radial site of the hand. It is one of the eight carpal bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The flat triangle-shaped bone that connects the humerus with the clavicle in the back of the shoulder. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The longest single nerve that is formed by the merging of the ventral rami of the L4, L5, and S1 in the pelvis and passes down the lower limb where it divides into the common peroneal and tibial nerves. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The white, opaque, fibrous, outer tunic of the eyeball, covering it entirely excepting the segment covered anteriorly by the cornea. It is essentially avascular but contains apertures for vessels, lymphatics, and nerves. It receives the tendons of insertion of the extraocular muscles and at the corneoscleral junction contains the canal of Schlemm. (From Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The musculocutaneous pouch that encloses the testicles. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Small glands located within the epidermis, and associated with the hair follicle, that produce and secrete an oily substance that lubricates the skin and hair. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 2ND DIAG; SECOND DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The second artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 2ND LPL; SECOND LEFT POSTEROLATERAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the second branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 2ND OM; SECOND OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The second artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 2ND RPL; SECOND RIGHT POSTEROLATERAL ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the second branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the two paired glands in the male genitourinary system, posterior to the bladder and superior to the prostate gland, that produces fructose-rich seminal fluid which is a component of semen. These glands join the ipsilateral ductus deferens to form the ejaculatory duct. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A muscle located at the posterior and medial aspect of the thigh that extends the hip joint, flexes the knee joint and assists in medially rotating the knee.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The region of the body between the neck and the upper arm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A ball-and-socket joint at the upper end of the humerus, located at the junction of humerus and scapula. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A recess, cavity, or channel. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An organ that constitutes the external surface of the body. It consists of the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the axilla, or underarm.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the head.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin portion of the lip that contains hair.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the neck.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The skin or integument surrounding the trunk of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bones that form the head, made up of the bones of the braincase and face. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The section of the intestines between the pylorus and cecum. The small intestine is approximately 20 feet long and consists of the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum. Its main function is to absorb nutrients from food as the food is transported to the large intestine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A movable fold suspended from the posterior border of the hard palate. (MeSH)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The undersurface of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eleventh cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bony projection arising from the posterior vertebral arch that serves for the attachment of muscles and ligaments.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An organ that is part of the hematopoietic and immune systems. It is composed of the white pulp and the red pulp and is surrounded by a capsule. It is located in the left hypochondriac region. Its functions include lymphocyte production, blood cell storage, and blood cell destruction. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area of the spleen through which the vessels and nerves enter or exit the organ. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An artery arising from the celiac trunk with four main branches that supply the spleen, stomach and pancreas.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the hilar region of the spleen. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The upper segment of the sternum, quadrangular in shape, as well as wider superiorly and narrower inferiorly. The sternal manubrium articulates with the clavicle and first two ribs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The synovial juncture between the medial end of the clavicle and the anterior segment of the sternum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The long, flat bone connecting with the cartilages of the first seven ribs and the clavicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An organ located under the diaphragm, between the liver and the spleen as well as between the esophagus and the small intestine. The stomach is the primary organ of food digestion. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the thoracic cavity between the lungs. It is bordered by the carina of the trachea, lower lobe bronchus on the left and the bronchus intermedius on the right. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The vein that drains the axillary vein and joins the internal jugular vein to form the brachiocephalic vein. It runs parallel to the subclavian artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Adipose tissue located under the dermis. It binds underlying structures with the skin. The subcutis is important in the regulation of temperature of the skin itself and the body. The size of this layer varies throughout the body and from subject to subject.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The area of the larynx below the vocal cords down to the trachea. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A body region relating to the area under or adjacent to the tongue.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located beneath the floor of the oral cavity. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A large cell mass extending forward, over the dorsal surface of the crus cerebri, from the rostral border of the pons into the subthalamic region. It is composed of a dorsal stratum of closely spaced pigmented cells, the pars compacta, and a larger ventral region of widely scattered cells, the pars reticulata. The pars compacta includes numerous cells that project forward to the striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen) and contain dopamine, which acts as the primary neurotransmitter at the synaptic endings. Other, apparently non-dopaminergic cells project to portions of the ventral nucleus of thalamus, the superior colliculus and reticular formation. The nigrostriatal projection is reciprocated by a striatonigral fiber system with multiple neurotransmitters, chief among which is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). The substantia nigra is involved in the metabolic disturbances associated with Parkinson's disease and Huntington's disease. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The plane synovial joint between the talus and calcaneus bones of the foot.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The small coiled tubular glands in the skin that produce and secrete sweat.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the femoral artery distal to the branching of the deep femoral artery that runs close to the skin.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in a superficial part of the body.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The large vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node which is located above the clavicle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The part of the brain above the tentorium cerebellum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A mass containing the cell bodies of sympathetic nerves. Sympathetic ganglia exist as paravertebral ganglia (located bilaterally adjacent to the spinal cord) or prevertebral ganglia (located close to the target organ).

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The first thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tenth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eleventh thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The twelfth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The second thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The third thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fourth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fifth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sixth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The seventh thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eighth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The ninth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The bone of the foot that connects with the tibia and fibula to form the ankle joint. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any one of the seven bones forming the instep of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A terminal branch of the external carotid artery that branches into the anterior and posterior temporal arteries. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A large irregular bone situated at the base and side of the skull, connected with the mandible via the temporomandibular joint. The temporal bone consists of the squamous, tympanic and petrous parts. The petrous portion of the temporal bone contains the vestibulocochlear organ of the inner ear. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Lower lateral part of the cerebral hemisphere. (MSH2001)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The joint between the head of the lower mandible and the temporal bone. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A laminar extension of the dura mater that lies between, and separates, the cerebrum and the cerebellum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An ovoid mass composed predominantly of gray substance and associated laminae of white substance. The thalamus is divided into anterior, medial, and lateral parts. The function of the thalamus is to relay sensory impulses and cerebellar and basal ganglia projections to the cerebral cortex. The thalamus is positioned within the posterior part of the diencephalon forming most of each lateral wall of the third ventricle. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A part of the lower limb, located between hip and knee. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 3RD DIAG; THIRD DIAGONAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The third artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 3RD OM; THIRD OBTUSE MARGINAL BRANCH ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: The third artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 3RD LPL; THIRD POSTEROLATERAL DESCENDING ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the third branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: 3RD RPL; THIRD RIGHT POSTEROLATERAL ARTERY SEGMENT
definition: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the third branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The section of the aorta between the lower border of the fourth dorsal vertebrae and the aortic opening in the diaphragm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cavity in the vertebrate body enclosed by the ribs between the diaphragm and the neck and containing the lungs and heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Lymph node located in the thoracic cavity. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Any of the vertebrae situated between the cervical and lumbar vertebrae.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The division of the body lying between the neck and the abdomen. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The narrow passage from the mouth to the cavity at the back of the mouth. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bi-lobed organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is located in the upper anterior portion of the chest, behind the sternum. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and fewer epithelial cells. Connective tissue septa separate the lobes into lobules. The lobules contain an outer portion (cortical zone) which is rich in lymphocytes and an inner portion (medullary zone) which is rich in epithelial cells. It is an organ essential for the development of the immune system. Its function is the maturation of the progenitor lymphoid cells to thymocytes and subsequently to mature T-cells. It reaches its greatest weight at puberty and subsequently begins to involute. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An endocrine gland located at the base of the neck that produces and secretes thyroxine and other hormones. Thyroxine is important for metabolic control. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The narrow, central portion of the thyroid gland that crosses the trachea anteriorly and connects the two lobes of the gland. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cone-like lobe of the thyroid gland that is located in the left side of the trachea. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cone-like lobe of the thyroid gland that is located in the right side of the trachea. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bone located between the femur and the tarsus, being part of the lower leg. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The triangular prismoid, elongated bony body of the tibia.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The blood vessels segment that includes the crural artery and the tibial artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A muscle that originates from the lateral condyle of tibia, spans the upper two-thirds of the lateral surface of the tibia, and is attached to the first cuneiform and metatarsal bones of the foot. It is a dorsiflexor of the ankle and invertor of the foot.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An arterial trunk that contains parts of the posterior tibial artery and fibular artery.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of the terminal digits of the foot. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A thin, horny translucent plate covering the end of each toe. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The muscular organ located in the floor of the mouth and serving as the principal organ of taste and modification of the voice in speech. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The two organs situated in the throat on either side of the narrow passage from the mouth to the pharynx. They are composed of lymphoid tissues. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The anatomic space in the root of a tooth that contains nerves, blood vessels, and connective tissue. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The fibrocartilaginous, mucous-lined tube passing from the larynx to the bronchi. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: An anatomical structure comprised of trachea, bronchi, and bronchioles that terminate with the alveolar ducts, sacs, and alveoli. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A combination of syndesmosis and synovial joints formed by the articulation of the talus with the navicular and the calcaneus with the cuboid.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A carpal bone on the thumb side of the hand that articulates with the 1st and 2nd metacarpals. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: One of a pair of flat, large, triangular muscles that extend from the external occipital protuberance and the medial third of the superior nuchal line of the occipital bone to the middle of the back. The trapezius muscle is involved in moving the shoulder and arm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A carpal bone located between the trapezium and capitate bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A carpal bone located between the lunate and pisiform bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A three-cusp valve of the heart that regulates the flow of blood between the right atrium and the right ventricle of the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
synonym: Fifth Cranial Nerve; Nervus Trigeminus; Trigeminal Nerve
definition: The fifth set of paired nerves of the face that emerge from the brain steam. These nerves have sensory and motor functions in the face, oral cavity, and nasal cavity. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A bony protrusion on the femoral bone to which muscles are attached. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The body excluding the head and neck and limbs. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The inner most layer of the blood vessel wall. The consistency of the intima will vary depending on the type of blood vessel, but will always have an endothelial layer with a basal lamina. It may contain collagen and elastic fibers. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A thin membrane that separates the external auditory canal from the middle ear. The movement of the tympanic membrane in response to air pressure changes in the external ear facilitates the transmission of sound energy by causing vibration of the ossicular chain. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The long bone that extends from the elbow to the lateral side of the carpus.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The prismatic, elongated bony body of the ulna.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The depression or scar on the abdomen that marks the former site of attachment of the umbilical cord. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A portion of the pancreas that extends behind the superior mesenteric artery and superior mesenteric vein. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A lymph node located in the upper region of the neck. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The sinuses and those parts of the respiratory system above the trachea. It includes the nares, nasopharynx, oropharynx, larynx, vocal cords, glottis and upper trachea.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The thick-walled tube that carries urine from each kidney to the bladder. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The tube carrying urine from the bladder to outside of the body. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the urethra that extends from the meatus to the membranous urethra. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the urethra that spans the corpus spongiosum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the urethra that is located on the posterior aspect of the urogenital diaphragm. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: That part of the male urethra that passes through the prostate gland. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The organs involved in the creation and excretion of urine. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A hollow, thick-walled, muscular organ located within the pelvic cavity of a woman. Within the uterus the fertilized egg implants and the fetus develops during pregnancy. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The pigmented layer of the eyeball between the tough, white outer coat of the eye and the retina. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The female genital canal, extending from the uterus to the vulva. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The 10th cranial nerve. The vagus is a mixed nerve which contains somatic afferents (from skin in back of the ear and the external auditory meatus), visceral afferents (from the pharynx, larynx, thorax, and abdomen), parasympathetic efferents (to the thorax and abdomen), and efferents to striated muscle (of the larynx and pharynx). (MSH2001)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: Duct carrying spermatozoa. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the quadriceps femoris muscle group that is underneath the Rectus Femoris muscle, spans and covers the upper two-thirds of the anterior and lateral surfaces of the femur, and inserts into the lateral border of the patella.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The largest muscle of the quadriceps femoris muscle group that extends laterally from the intertrochanteric line of the femur to the lateral aspects of the quadriceps femoris tendon and patella.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The portion of the quadriceps femoris muscle group that extends medially from the intertrochanteric line of the femur to the medial aspects of the quadriceps femoris tendon and patella. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A blood vessel that carries blood towards the heart.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A large vein which returns blood from the head, neck and extremities to the heart. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A series of bones, muscles, tendons, and other tissues reaching from the base of the skull to the tailbone. The vertebral column forms the axis of the skeleton and encloses as well as protects the spinal cord and the fluid surrounding the spinal cord. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The eighth cranial nerve.

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A pair of small bands of muscle that stretch from the thyroid cartilage in front to the arytenoid cartilage in back of the larynx. The vocal cords help prevent food entering the lungs and produce sound through vibration. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A thin, paired or unpaired, trapezoidal bone of the skull located in the floor of the nasal cavity. The vomer forms the posterior and inferior parts of the nasal septum. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The external, visible part of the female genitalia surrounding the urethral and vaginal opening. The vulva includes the clitoris and inner as well as outer labia. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The abdominal circumference at the navel. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The ring of lymphoid tissue located in the pharynx, consisting of the pharyngeal, tubal, palatine, and lingual tonsils. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: A joint between the distal end of the radius and the proximal row of carpal bones. (NCI)

name: Anatomical Location
definition: The cartilage just below the sternal body. (NCI)

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: A finding of aviremia at a specified timepoint, early during the treatment period.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: A finding of aviremia at a predetermined time point after the end of planned or actual treatment.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: The subject becomes viremic during the treatment period after a period of treatment-induced aviremia or has an increase in viral load from nadir above a predetermined threshold during the treatment period.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: A recurrence of the same virus after a finding of aviremia at the end of planned or actual treatment.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: A finding of aviremia at the end of the planned or actual end of treatment period.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: A finding of viremia at or after end of planned or actual treatment, excluding treatment discontinuations for non-virologic reasons.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: The subject remains viremic during the treatment period.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: The subject remains viremic during the treatment period and the decrease in viral load from baseline at a specified timepoint is below or equal to a predetermined threshold.

name: Anti-Viral Outcome of Treatment
definition: The subject remains viremic during the treatment period and the decrease in viral load from baseline at a specified timepoint is above a predetermined threshold.

name: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Classification
definition: Ordinary physical activity, such as walking or climbing stairs, does not cause angina. Angina occurs with strenuous, rapid, or prolonged exertion at work or recreation.
term: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Grading Scale Class I

name: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Classification
definition: Slight limitation of ordinary activity. Angina occurs on walking or climbing stairs rapidly, walking uphill, walking or climbing stairs after meals, or in cold, in wind, or under emotional stress, or only during the few hours after awakening. Angina occurs on walking more than 2 blocks on the level and climbing more than 1 flight of ordinary stairs at a normal pace and in normal conditions.
term: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Grading Scale Class II

name: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Classification
definition: Marked limitations of ordinary physical activity. Angina occurs on walking 1 to 2 blocks on the level and climbing 1 flight of stairs in normal conditions and at a normal pace.
term: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Grading Scale Class III

name: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Classification
definition: Inability to perform any physical activity without discomfort - anginal symptoms may be present at rest.
term: Canadian Cardiovascular Society Grading Scale Class IV

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: The intended recipient of a heart transplant.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: An episode of cardiac arrest or arrhythmia where the etiology was unknown.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A disease of the heart muscle or myocardium proper. Cardiomyopathies may be classified as either primary or secondary, on the basis of etiology, or on the pathophysiology of the lesion: hypertrophic, dilated, or restrictive.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A longstanding, complete blockage of a vessel.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: The subject contributing a heart for a cardiac transplant.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: The battery that supplies the device has reached the end of its life.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: There is a faulty connector/header in the device.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: GENERATOR IS BEING REPLACED AT THE TIME OF LEAD REVISION
definition: A cardiac lead requires revision, at which time the generator to the device will be replaced.
term: Cardiac Device Generator is Being Replaced at Time of Lead Revision

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: The device has a generator malfunction.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: IMMEDIATE PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (STEMI)
definition: An immediate percutaneous coronary intervention is necessary for a myocardial infarction that presents with ST segment elevation.
term: Immediate Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A disorder resulting from the presence and activity of a microbial, viral, or parasitic agent. It can be transmitted by direct or indirect contact. (NCI)

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A cardiac lead has damaged local tissue enough to require treatment.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: The degree of impairment of the left cardiac ventricle to contract efficiently.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: An imperative issued by the manufacturer of a device that the device needs to be returned to a designated source for repair or replacement.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: MANUFACTURER RECOGNIZED A RECURRING PERFORMANCE FAILURE
definition: The device manufacturer had recognized a recurrent performance failure in the device.
term: Manufacturer Recognized a Recurring Performance Failure

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: MEDICAL CONDITION OR PROCEDURE AFFECTS IMPLANTATION SITE
definition: The medical condition or the procedure affects the device implantation site.
term: Medical Condition or Procedure Affects Implantation Site

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: MEDICAL OR SURGICAL PROCEDURE REQUIRING RELOCATION OF LEAD
definition: An intended medical or surgical procedure necessitates the relocation of a cardiac lead.
term: Medical or Surgical Procedure Requiring Relocation of Lead

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR HIGH RISK NON-ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION OR UNSTABLE ANGINA
definition: Includes patients with unstable angina or Non-STEMI who have high risk features for short-term risk of death or nonfatal MI. High risk features includes at least one of the following: history of accelerating tempo of ischemic symptoms in preceding 48 hours; character of pain - prolonged ongoing (greater than 20 minutes) rest pain; clinical findings - pulmonary edema, most likely due to ischemia or new or worsening mitral regurgitation murmur; or S3 or new worsening rales or Hypotension, bradycardia, tachycardia or age greater than 75 years; ECG - angina at rest with transient ST-segment changes greater than 0.5 mm or bundle-branch block, new or presumed new or sustained ventricular tachycardia; cardiac markers - NSTEMI patients with elevated cardiac TnT, Tnl, or CK-MB.
term: Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for High Risk Non-ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction or Unstable Angina

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (STEMI) (STABLE AFTER SUCCESSFUL FULL-DOSE THROMBOLYTICS)
definition: A percutaneous coronary intervention is necessary for a myocardial infarction that presents with ST segment elevation and the subject does not have recurrent or persistent symptoms, symptoms of heart failure or ventricular arrhythmia after a successful dose of thrombolytic therapy.
term: Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction-Stable After Successful Full-Dose Thrombolytic Therapy

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (STEMI) (STABLE, >12 HRS FROM SYMPTOM ONSET)
definition: A percutaneous coronary intervention is necessary for a myocardial infarction that presents with ST segment elevation and the subject does not have recurrent or persistent symptoms, symptoms of heart failure or ventricular arrhythmia. The presentation is past twelve hours since onset of symptoms.
term: Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction-Stable-Over 12 Hours From Symptom Onset

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (STEMI) (UNSTABLE, >12 HRS FROM SYMPTOM ONSET)
definition: A percutaneous coronary intervention is necessary for a myocardial infarction that presents with ST segment elevation and the subject has recurrent or persistent symptoms, symptoms of heart failure or ventricular arrhythmia. The presentation is past twelve hours since onset of symptoms.
term: Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction-Unstable-Over 12 Hours From Symptom Onset

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A procedure to evaluate the health of the an individual after receiving a heart transplant.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A procedure to evaluate the health of the cardiac system to determine feasibility of a non-cardiac related surgical procedure.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A procedure performed to avoid the first occurrence of a disease condition.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: RESCUE PERCUTANEOUS CORONARY INTERVENTION (PCI) FOR ST ELEVATION MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (STEMI) (AFTER FAILED FULL-DOSE THROMBOLYTICS)
definition: A percutaneous coronary intervention is imperative for a myocardial infarction that presents with ST segment elevation after an unsatisfactory response to a full dose of thrombolytic therapy.
term: Rescue Percutaneous Coronary Intervention for ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction After Failed Full-Dose Thrombolytic Therapy

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A procedure performed to avoid a subsequent occurrence of a disease condition.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: Ventricular tachycardia that occurs without provocation and does not resolve spontaneously.
term: Spontaneous Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A subsequent Percutaneous Coronary Intervention in a planned series of procedures, where the first PCI could have been during a prior admission, or during this admission.

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: A sudden loss of consciousness with loss of postural tone not related to anesthesia with high risk characteristics. High risk characteristics include non-ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy, or ischemic heart disease with significant ventricular dysfunction, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, Brugada Syndrome, or Long QT Syndrome.
term: Syncope with High Risk Cardiac Characteristics

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: Sudden loss of consciousness with loss of postural tone not related to anesthesia with ventricular tachycardia (VT) that can be induced during an electrophysiological study.
term: Syncope with Inducible Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
value: UPGRADE TO A DEVICE WITH ADDITIONAL PACING CAPABILITIES
definition: A device with additional pacing capabilities is replacing the current device.
term: Upgrade to Cardiac Device with Additional Pacing Capabilities

name: Cardiac Procedure Indication
definition: Ventricular Fibrillation is characterized by rapid, usually more than 300 bpm (cycle length: 180 ms or less), grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude.

name: Cardiac Rhythm Device Failure Manifestation
definition: The cardiac rhythm device malfunction affected atrial pacing.

name: Cardiac Rhythm Device Failure Manifestation
definition: The cardiac rhythm device malfunction affected the defibrillator.

name: Cardiac Rhythm Device Failure Manifestation
definition: The cardiac rhythm device malfunction affected the left ventricular (LV) pacing.

name: Cardiac Rhythm Device Failure Manifestation
definition: The cardiac rhythm device malfunction affected the right ventricular (RV) pacing.

name: Cardiac Valvular Regurgitation Severity
definition: Evidence of mild retrograde blood flow through the valve(s) of the heart.

name: Cardiac Valvular Regurgitation Severity
definition: Evidence of moderate retrograde blood flow through the valve(s) of the heart.

name: Cardiac Valvular Regurgitation Severity
definition: No evidence of any retrograde blood flow through the valve(s) in the heart.

name: Cardiac Valvular Regurgitation Severity
definition: Evidence of severe retrograde blood flow through the valve(s) of the heart.

name: Cardiac Valvular Stenosis Severity
definition: The cardiac valve orifice is abnormally narrow, to a mild degree.

name: Cardiac Valvular Stenosis Severity
definition: The cardiac valve orifice is abnormally narrow, to a moderate degree.

name: Cardiac Valvular Stenosis Severity
definition: The cardiac valve orifice is not abnormally narrow.

name: Cardiac Valvular Stenosis Severity
definition: The cardiac valve orifice is abnormally narrow, to a severe degree.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: A method used to create an image of blood vessels.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Initiation or intensification of orally administered medication(s) that promote diuresis to treat heart failure.
term: Oral Diuretic Therapy Augmentation for Heart Failure

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: A postmortem examination of the body.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
value: CLINICALLY SIGNIFICANT OR RAPID WEIGHT GAIN
definition: Weight gain thought to be related to fluid retention.
term: Weight Gain Due to Fluid Retention

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Angiographic evidence of new or worse greater than or equal to 70 percent lesion and/or thrombus in an epicardial coronary artery believed to be responsible for the myocardial ischemic symptoms/signs. (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Need for coronary revascularization procedure (PCI or CABG) for the presumed culprit lesion(s). This criterion would be fulfilled if revascularization was undertaken during the unscheduled hospitalization, or subsequent to transfer to another institution without interceding home discharge. (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Reduced ability to withstand or participate in activities that induce physical or mental exertion.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Includes dyspnea on exertion, dyspnea at rest, orthopnea, and paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Unusual tiredness and inability to perform usual activities.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: An event where the patient is admitted to the hospital with a primary diagnosis of heart failure (HF), where the length of stay is at least 24 hours (or extends over a calendar date), where the patient exhibits new or worsening symptoms of HF on presentation, has objective evidence of new or worsening HF, and receives initiation or intensification of treatment specifically for HF. (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: An acute episode of focal or global cerebral or spinal dysfunction caused by intraparenchymal, intraventricular, or subarachnoid hemorrhage.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Biomarker increase (B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP)/ N-terminal pro-BNP (NT-proBNP)) consistent with decompensation of heart failure (such as BNP greater than 500 pg/mL or NT-proBNP greater than 2,000 pg/mL). In patients with chronically elevated natriuretic peptides, a significant increase above baseline is required. (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)
term: Increase in B-type Natriuretic Peptide or N-terminal pro-B-type Natriuretic Peptide

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
value: INCREASED JUGULAR VENOUS PRESSURE OR HEPATOJUGULAR REFLUX
definition: Increase in the estimated height of the mean jugular venous waveform above the right atrium in cm.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Intra-abdominal fluid accumulation as determined by physical examination (in the absence of primary hepatic disease).

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Definite evidence of inducible myocardial ischemia believed to be responsible for the myocardial ischemic symptoms/signs, demonstrated by any of the following: a) an early positive exercise stress test, defined as ST elevation of greater than or equal to 2 mm ST depression prior to 5 mets, b) stress echocardiography (reversible wall motion abnormality), c) myocardial scintigraphy (reversible perfusion defect), d) MRI (myocardial perfusion deficit under pharmacologic stress). (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
value: INTRAVENOUS DIURETIC, INOTROPE, OR VASODILATOR THERAPY
definition: Initiation or intensification of medication(s) administered by vein to treat heart failure, to increase the production of urine, increase cardiac performance, and/or reduce cardiac preload or afterload.
term: Intravenous Diuretic, Inotropic or Vasodilator Augmentation for Heart Failure

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
value: INVASIVE DIAGNOSTIC EVIDENCE OF HEART FAILURE
definition: Invasive diagnostic evidence with right heart catheterization showing a pulmonary capillary wedge pressure (pulmonary artery occlusion pressure) greater than or equal to 18 mmHg, central venous pressure greater than or equal to 12 mmHg, or a cardiac index less than 2.2 L/min/m2. (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)
term: Heart Failure by Invasive Diagnostic Technique

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Ischemic stroke is defined as an acute episode of focal cerebral, spinal, or retinal dysfunction caused by infarction of central nervous system tissue.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Angiographic loss of patency of a side branch.
term: Loss of Patency of Side Branch

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Angiographic loss of patency of a major epicardial vessel.
term: Loss of Patency of Major Vessel

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Mechanical circulatory support (e.g., intra-aortic balloon pump, ventricular assist device, extracorporeal membrane oxygenation, total artificial heart) or mechanical fluid removal (e.g., ultrafiltration, hemofiltration, dialysis). (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Non-invasive imaging evidence of a loss of viable myocardium when compared with the most recent previous non-invasive imaging study.
term: New Loss of Viable Myocardium by Non-invasive Imaging Technique

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Non-invasive imaging evidence of a decrease in regional wall motion contractility compared with the most recent previous non-invasive imaging study.
term: New Regional Wall Motion Abnormality by Non-invasive Imaging Technique

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
value: NON-INVASIVE DIAGNOSTIC EVIDENCE OF HEART FAILURE
definition: Non-invasive diagnostic evidence of clinically significant elevated left- or right-sided ventricular filling pressure or low cardiac output. For example, echocardiographic criteria could include: E/e' greater than 15 or D-dominant pulmonary venous inflow pattern, plethoric inferior vena cava with minimal collapse on inspiration, or decreased left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) minute stroke distance (time velocity integral (TVI)). (Hicks KA, Tcheng JE, Bozkurt B, Chaitman BR, Cutlip DE, Farb A, Fonarow GC, Jacobs JP, Jaff MR, Lichtman JH, Limacher MC, Mahaffey KW, Mehran, R, Nissen SE, Smith EE, Targum SL. 2014 ACC/AHA Key Data Elements and Definitions For Cardiovascular Endpoint Events In Clinical Trials: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Data Standards (Writing Committee to Develop Cardiovascular End Points Data Standards) J Am Coll Cardiol 2014; In Press)
term: Heart Failure by Non-invasive Diagnostic Technique

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Increased tissue fluid indicated by perceptible pitting indentation on lower leg, foot or sacrum after palpation.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Abnormal breath sounds caused by the accumulation of fluid in the lungs.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Imaging findings consistent with increased intravascular blood volume in the lungs.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: New or worsening ST or T wave changes on resting ECG (in the absence of confounders, such as LBBB or LVH), defined as either: a) Transient ST elevation (duration less than 20 minutes): new ST elevation at the J point in any two contiguous leads (other than leads V2-V3) of greater than or equal to 0.1 mV. In leads V2-V3, the following cut-points apply: greater than or equal to 0.2 mV in men greater than or equal to 40 years, greater than or equal to 0.25 mV in men less than 40 years, and greater than or equal to 0.15 mV in women, or b) ST depression and T-wave changes: new horizontal or down-sloping ST depression greater than or equal to 0.05 mV in two contiguous leads and/or new T inversion greater than or equal to 0.3 mV in two contiguous leads with prominent R wave or R/S ratio greater than 1.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Presence of mid-diastolic heart sound.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Angiographic reduction of flow into the coronary microcirculation.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Spontaneous clinical syndrome related to atherosclerotic plaque rupture, ulceration, fissuring, erosion, or dissection, with resulting intraluminal thrombus, and leading to decreased myocardial blood flow or distal platelet emboli with ensuing myocyte necrosis. This classification requires a) detection of a rise and/or fall of cardiac biomarker values [preferably cardiac troponin (cTn)] with at least one value greater than 99th percentile of the upper reference limit (URL) and b) at least one of the following: symptoms of myocardial ischemia; new or presumed new significant ST-segment-T wave (ST-T) changes or new left bundle branch block (LBBB) on the ECG; development of pathological Q waves on the ECG; imaging evidence of new loss of viable myocardium or new regional wall motion abnormality; identification of an intracoronary thrombus by angiography or autopsy. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 1 Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Ischemic imbalance: Spontaneous clinical syndrome where a condition other than coronary artery disease contributes to an imbalance between myocardial oxygen supply and/or demand, e.g. coronary endothelial dysfunction, coronary artery spasm, coronary embolism, tachy-/brady-arrhythmias, anemia, respiratory failure, hypotension, and hypertension with or without left ventricular hypertrophy. This classification requires detection of a rise and/or fall of cardiac biomarker values [preferably cardiac troponin (cTn)] with at least one value greater than 99th percentile of the upper reference limit (URL) and b) at least one of the following: symptoms of myocardial ischemia; new or presumed new significant ST-segment-T wave (ST-T) changes or new left bundle branch block (LBBB) on the ECG; development of pathological Q waves on the ECG; imaging evidence of new loss of viable myocardium or new regional wall motion abnormality. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 2 Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Death, No Biomarkers: Death where symptoms suggestive of myocardial ischemia are present, and with (presumed) new ischemic changes or new LBBB on ECG, but where death occurs before cardiac biomarkers can be obtained, or before cardiac biomarker values could rise. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 3 Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: PCI Related: PCI Related Myocardial infarction associated with and occurring within 48h of percutaneous coronary intervention, with elevation of cardiac biomarker values to greater than 5x 99th percentile of the upper reference limit (URL) in patients with normal baseline values (less than or equal to 99th percentile URL), or a rise of cardiac biomarker values greater than or equal to 20% if the baseline values are elevated and are stable or falling. This classification also requires at least one of the following: symptoms of myocardial ischemia; new ischemic ECG changes or new LBBB; angiographic loss of patency of a major coronary artery or a side branch or persistent slow- or no-flow or embolization; imaging evidence of new loss of viable myocardium or new regional wall motion abnormality. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 4A Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Stent Thrombosis: Myocardial infarction associated with stent thrombosis as detected by coronary angiography or at autopsy, where symptoms suggestive of myocardial ischemia are present, and with a rise and/or fall of cardiac biomarkers values, with at least one value greater than 99th percentile of the upper reference limit. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 4B Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: Stent Restenosis: Myocardial infarction associated with stent restenosis as detected by coronary angiography or at autopsy, occurring more than 48h after percutaneous coronary intervention, without evidence of stent thrombosis but with symptoms suggestive of myocardial ischemia, and with elevation of cardiac biomarker values to greater than 99th percentile of the upper reference limit (URL). This classification also requires the following: does not meet criteria for any other classification of myocardial infarction; presence of a greater than or equal to 50 percent stenosis at the site of previous successful stent PCI. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 4C Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: CABG Related: Myocardial infarction associated with and occurring within 48h of coronary artery bypass graft surgery, with elevation of cardiac biomarker values to greater than 10x 99th percentile of the upper reference limit (URL) in patients with normal baseline cardiac biomarker values (less than or equal to 99th percentile URL). This classification also requires at least one of the following: new pathologic Q waves or new LBBB on ECG; angiographic new graft or new native coronary artery occlusion; imaging evidence of new loss of viable myocardium or new regional wall motion abnormality. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)
term: Joint Task Force Type 5 Myocardial Infarction

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
definition: An acute episode of focal or global neurological dysfunction caused by presumed brain, spinal cord, or retinal vascular injury as a result of hemorrhage or infarction but with insufficient information to allow categorization as ischemic or hemorrhagic.

name: Cardiovascular Findings About Results
