synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate High Lateral Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE INFERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate Inferior Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE LATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate Lateral Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE POSTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate Posterior Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE SEPTAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate Septal Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
synonym: Old Or Age Indeterminate Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. No specification is provided for localization.
term: Old Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: OLD OR AGE UNDETERMINED RIGHT VENTRICULAR MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
definition: An electrocardiographic finding, in the presence of an old or age indeterminate inferior wall myocardial infarction, of Q waves greater than or equal to 40 ms in duration in the right ventricular leads V4R through V6R.
term: Old or Age Indeterminate Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more electrodes are incorrectly placed but further details are not provided.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding for the P wave that is atypical either for the shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity. Abnormality of the P wave signifies aberrant propagation of the electrical impulse through the atria. (NCI)
term: P Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of P waves with two peaks longer in duration than normal and amplitude greater than normal.
term: P Wave Notched by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: AV dual-paced complex(es) or rhythm; Paced Atrial And Ventricular Rhythm
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which both the atrial and ventricular rhythm are controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Atrial-paced complex(es) or rhythm; Paced Atrial Rhythm
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the atrial rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Atrial and/or Ventricular Paced Rhythm; Paced Rhythm
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the cardiac rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Paced Ventricular Rhythm; Ventricular-paced complex(es) or rhythm
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the ventricular rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of the sudden onset of transient AV block, which is often associated with preexisting conduction disorders.
term: Paroxysmal Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An episodic form of ventricular tachycardia, with abrupt onset and termination. (NCI)
term: Paroxysmal Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an RR interval which exceeds a predefined duration threshold, regardless of the underlying rhythm.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an RR interval with duration greater than 3.0 seconds, regardless of the underlying rhythm.
term: Pause Greater Than Three Seconds by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording that does not show proper quality for reasons that are not otherwise described.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a lack of progression of R wave height across precordial leads.
term: Poor R Wave Progression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Posterior MI; Posterior Wall Myocardial Infarction
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present.
term: Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of PR segment depression below the iso-electric line in multiple precordial and/or limb leads.
term: PR Segment Depression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding characterized by a premature activation of the whole or some part of the ventricle. The PR interval is usually shortened and delta waves are frequently present.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V1 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V1.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V1 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V2 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V2.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V2 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V3 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V3.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V3 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V4 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V4.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V4 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V5 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V5.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V5 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V6 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V6.
term: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V6 by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more precordial electrodes are placed incorrectly with respect to the standard chest electrode positions resulting in improper representation of the affected leads.
term: Incorrectly Positioned Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which two or more of the precordial electrodes are switched resulting in improper representation of the affected leads.
term: Interchanged Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: APC; Atrial premature complex(es); PAC; Premature atrial complex; SVE; Supraventricular Extra Beat
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the atria and not specifically in the sinus node. The P wave morphology of these complexes is often different from a sinus P wave and the RR intervals preceding these complexes is also shorter than those of the regular beats.
term: Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Atrial premature complexes, nonconducted; Non-conducted SVE; Premature Atrial Complexes Blocked; Premature Atrial Complexes Non-conducted
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which are not conducted to the ventricle, and which are not followed by a QRS complex.
term: Blocked Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Multifocal SVE; Multifocal Supraventricular Extra Beats; Premature Atrial Complexes Multiform
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have 2 or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one atrial site.
term: Multifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one atrial site.
term: Unifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: PVC; VE; VPC; Ventricular Extra Beat; Ventricular premature complex(es)
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the ventricles. The QRS morphology of these complexes is different from those of supraventricular origin. The QRS duration is often longer and the RR interval preceding the complexes is usually shorter than that of supraventricular beats.
term: Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Interpolated VE; Interpolated VPC; Interpolated Ventricular Extra Beat; Premature Ventricular Complexes Interpolated
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a premature ventricular complex which occurs between two normal QRS complexes which have normal timing.
term: Interpolated Premature Ventricular Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Multifocal VES; Multifocal VPCS; Multifocal Ventricular Extra Beats; Premature Ventricular Complexes Multifocal
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have two or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one ventricular site.
term: Multifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Premature Ventricular Complexes Unifocal; Unifocal VES; Unifocal VPCS; Unifocal Ventricular Extra Beats
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one ventricular site.
term: Unifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval not corrected for heart rate is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
term: Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a prolonged ST segment, resulting in a long QT interval, without lengthening of the T wave duration.
term: Prolonged ST Segment by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Left-axis deviation; Q Axis, Left axis deviation; QRS axis, left axis deviation
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a frontal plane QRS axis from -30 to -90 degrees.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Q Axis, Right axis deviation; QRS axis, right axis deviation; Right-axis deviation
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a frontal plane QRS axis from +90 to +180 degrees.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a non-specific abnormality of the QRS complex, which is atypical in shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity.
term: QRS Complex Abnormality by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QTc interval corrected for heart rate is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
term: Corrected Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic artifact or recording error with unknown origin or which is not described otherwise.
term: Quality Problem Not Otherwise Specified by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the R wave of a premature ventricular complex occurs on top of the T wave of the preceding beat.
term: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an R wave variant in which there is a small deflection of the R wave, with changing polarity, within the QRS complex. (NCI)
term: R Wave Notched by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormality of T wave duration or morphology or of early repolarization.

name: ECG Result
value: REPOLARIZATION ABNORMALITY SECONDARY TO VENTRICULAR HYPERTROPHY
synonym: Repolarization Abnormality Secondary To Ventricular Hypertrophy; ST-T change due to ventricular hypertrophy
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST depression and T wave inversion in the presence of increased QRS amplitude which are thought to be due to left ventricular hypertrophy.
term: Repolarization Abnormality Secondary To Ventricular Hypertrophy

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting underlying hypertrophy or dilatation of the right atrium. Electrocardiographic criteria used for the diagnosis of right atrial abnormality may include a peaked p wave greater than 2.5 millimeters in amplitude in the inferior leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Result
synonym: Complete RBBB; Right bundle branch block; Right bundle-branch block
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the right ventricle, manifest by a widened initial portion of the QRS in V1 and V2, a widened S wave in V5, V6, I and aVL, and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms. An RsR' complex is typically present in leads V1 and V2.
term: Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Right Ventricular Conduction Delay; Right Ventricular Delay
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is evidence that electrical transmission through the right ventricle is impaired with a maximal QRS duration of 110 ms and which does not meet the criteria for Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block.
term: Right Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied right ventricle, characterized by large R wave amplitudes in the right precordial leads and secondary findings of right atrial enlargement, right axis deviation, and typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion in the right precordial leads.
term: Right Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are two R waves, which are two deflections above the baseline resulting from a single ventricular depolarization. The first upward deflection in the complex is the R wave. The S is the first downward deflection. A second upward deflection is called the R-prime wave.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting an infarction in the anatomic location of the cardiac septum. (NCI)
term: Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormally short PR interval. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
term: Short PR Interval by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a QT interval corrected for heart rate that is shorter than the lower limit of normal. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a short or absent ST segment, resulting in a short QT interval, without changes in T wave morphology.
term: Short ST Segment by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: SA Block; Sinoatrial Block; Sinoatrial exit block
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which impaired conduction or automaticity within the sinus node results in the failure of impulse transmission from the sinoatrial node. This is manifest as dropped P waves during sinus rhythm.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Sinus arrest/pause; Sinus pause or arrest
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which a failure of impulse formation or conduction in the sinus node produces prolongation of the P-P interval or dropped P waves. The threshold for the prolongation of the P-P interval is not well defined.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the sinus rate fluctuates with the respiratory cycle.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally slow heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial rhythm which originates from the sinoatrial node that is considered normal for the population.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment depression below the baseline, often described as up sloping, down sloping or horizontal. (NCI)
term: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment elevation above the baseline. (NCI)
term: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST elevation which is concave upwards, and which is often accompanied by PR segment depression.
term: ST Elevation Pericarditis by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature atrial complexes occur sequentially.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a tachycardia which does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system. There is an abnormally high heart rate and QRS complexes are typically narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present.

name: ECG Result
value: SUSPECT LIMB ELECTRODES REVERSED, INTERPRETATION ASSUMES NO REVERSAL
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, but for which an interpretation is performed as though the lead placement is correct.
term: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes No Reversal by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
value: SUSPECT LIMB ELECTRODES REVERSED, INTERPRETATION ASSUMES REVERSAL
definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, and for which an interpretation is performed as though the leads have in fact been interchanged.
term: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes Reversal by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular tachycardia greater than 30 seconds in duration. (NCI)
term: Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are variations in the shape, amplitude, or direction of the T wave from one beat to the next.
term: T Wave Alternans by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an inversion of the T wave from the expected axis. (NCI)
term: T Wave Inversion by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears increased in amplitude and cresting at a point. (NCI)
term: T Wave Peaked by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a T wave with both positive and negative components.
term: T Waves Biphasic by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears decreased in amplitude. (NCI)
term: T Waves Flat by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Torsades de pointes; Ventricular tachycardia, torsades de pointes
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atypical rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic rotation of the QRS complex around the isoelectric baseline, occurring in the setting of a prolonged QT interval. In addition, the QRS complex displays a periodic waxing and waning of amplitude on the electrogram.
term: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of U waves which have increased amplitude, are inverted, or merged with the preceding T wave.
term: U Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: A statement indicating the inability to digitize a paper ECG.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm whose mechanism cannot be determined from the ECG.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rhythm which does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system, but whose specific electrophysiologic mechanism cannot be determined from the ECG. The QRS complexes are typically narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present.
term: Undetermined Supraventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a normal QRS complex followed by a premature ventricular complex for 3 or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal QRS complexes in a 1-1 ratio.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature ventricular complexes occur sequentially.

name: ECG Result
synonym: Ventricular Escape Beat; Ventricular escape complex(es)
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a compensatory ventricular complex that occurs following a prolonged RR interval.
term: Ventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm.

name: ECG Result
definition: A ventricular tachyarrhythmia characterized by a high ventricular rate (180 to 250 beats per minute) with a regular rhythm. The electrocardiogram shows large oscillating sine wave-like complexes occurring as a result of QRS complexes and T waves being merged. The P wave is not visible. (NCI)

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of normal sinus rhythm coexisting with a regular ectopic ventricular rhythm.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular organ with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a uniform morphology.
term: Monomorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
synonym: Ventricular tachycardia, polymorphic; Ventricular tachycardia, polymorphous
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a variable morphology and often rate.
term: Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of two normal QRS complexes followed by a premature ventricular complex for 3 or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal QRS complexes in a 2-1 ratio.

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically below 100 beats per minute.
term: Wandering Atrial Pacemaker by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive wide QRS complexes of uncertain origin with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used).
term: Wide QRS Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: ECG Result
definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular pre-excitation. The syndrome is characterized by a short PR interval and a long QRS interval with a delta wave.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic finding assessment of new or presumed new significant ST-segment-T wave (ST-T) changes or new left bundle branch block consistent with acute myocardial ischemia. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012)
term: Acute Myocardial Ischemia by ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of cardiac atrioventricular conduction.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of mean cardiac electrical vector and the ECG voltage.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of chamber hypertrophy or enlargement.
term: Chamber Hypertrophy or Enlargement ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the median rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A comparative interpretation of an ECG relative to a previous (comparator) ECG. The definition of the comparator ECG may be specified elsewhere. Common comparator result values include improved, no change, deteriorated.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the maximum ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the minimum ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the mean ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of a heart rate derived from a single RR interval (interval between two consecutive QRS complexes).
term: Single Beat RR Extrapolated Heart Rate by ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the median rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median number of cycles of contraction and subsequent relaxation of the heart, usually expressed as beats per minute, obtained from a set of measurements of the heart rate.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An act or process of elucidation; explication, or explanation of the meaning of the event or thing via the assignment of objects from the domain to the constants of a formal language, truth-values to the proposition symbols, truth-functions to the connectives, other functions to the function symbols, and extensions to the predicates, if any. The assignments are result of human logic application and are not native to the symbols of the formal language.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of intraventricular and intra-atrial conduction.
term: Intraventricular and Intraatrial Conduction ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate JT value based on the measurement of JT intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: JTcB = JT/SqRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the JT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A JTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A JTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: JTcF = JT/CubeRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the JT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A JTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A JTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. The linear correction formula uses population-based data obtained and validated using a large cohort of subjects. Using this method, the corrected JT interval is independent of the ventricular rate. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization). (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization). (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization). (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate J-Tpeak value based on the measurement of J-Tpeak intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the J point to the peak of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the J point to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of findings suggestive of myocardial infarction.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic finding assessment of new or presumed new pathologic Q waves suggestive of myocardial infarction. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012).

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of presence of artificial electronic pacing.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate PP value based on the measurement of PP intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the interval between the onsets of two consecutive P waves.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate PR value based on the measurement of PR intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the P wave to the onset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) from the onset of atrial depolarization to the completion of atrial depolarization (length of the P wave), obtained from a set of measurements of the time from beginning to end of atrial depolarization. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) height (usually measured in mm) of the maximum deflection from baseline of the P wave (representing atrial depolarization), obtained from a set of measurements of the P wave, from a single lead or set of leads. Typically this measurement is obtained by analysis of Lead II. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate P wave duration value based on the measurement of P wave duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the P wave to the offset of the P wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate P wave amplitude value based on the measurement of P wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the P wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the P wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the P wave from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate QRS value based on the measurement of QRS intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the QRS interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QRS interval. The QRS interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the QRS complex, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the QRS interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QRS interval while the ventricle rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from a mechanical cardiac pacemaker. The QRS interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the QRS complex, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median duration (time) of the QRS interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QRS interval. The QRS interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the QRS complex, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the QRS complex to the offset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the QRS complex from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate paced QRS duration value based on the measurement of paced QRS duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
synonym: QRS Duration, Ventr. Paced, Single Beat
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the paced QRS complex to the offset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.
term: Paced Ventricular Single Beat QRS Duration

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate QT value based on the measurement of QT intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The time interval between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave in the cardiac cycle as corrected with a non-specified correction formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the QT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the QT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: QTcB = QT/SqRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the QT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A QTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A QTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the QT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the QT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: QTcF = QT/CubeRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the QT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A QTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median duration (time) of the QTc interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval and corrected using the Fridericia's correction Formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A QTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the QT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the QT interval across a range of rates. The linear correction formula uses population-based data obtained and validated using a large cohort of subjects. This method theoretically corrects the QT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
synonym: QTcV - Van de Water's Correction Formula
definition: A mathematic formula defined as: QTcV = QT-0.087[(60/Heart Rate)-1](seconds). It permits comparison of the QT interval across a range of rates, while accounting for the progressive shortening of the QT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases. (NCI)
term: QTcV - Van de Water's Correction Formula

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the QRS complex to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate Q wave amplitude value based on the measurement of Q wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the Q wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the Q wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of cardiac rhythm not otherwise specified.
term: Rhythm Not Otherwise Specified ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate RR value based on the measurement of RR intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the RR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the RR interval. The RR interval is defined as the time between successive peaks of the R wave and can be used to measure the ventricular rate. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The median duration (time) of the RR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the RR interval. The RR interval is defined as the time between successive peaks of the R wave and can be used to measure the ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the interval between two consecutive R waves. If R waves are not present, this measurement may utilize the interval between the most easily identified components of the QRS complex within two consecutive beats.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate RS wave amplitude value based on measurements from multiple beats from a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) amplitude (usually in mm) of the summation of the R and S waves, obtained from a set of measurements of the R and S waves, in a particular lead or set of leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the sum of the amplitudes of the R and S waves, obtained from a single beat in one particular lead or set of leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate R wave amplitude value based on the measurement of R wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the R wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the R wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) amplitude (usually in mm) of the R wave, obtained from a set of measurements of the R wave, in a particular lead or set of leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of sinus node rhythms and arrhythmias.
term: Sinus Node Rhythm and Arrhythmia ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of supraventricular arrhythmias excluding tachycardias.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of supraventricular tachyarrhythmias.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate ST segment depression value based on the measurement of ST segment depression from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum depression (negative deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the depression of the ST segment. (NCI)
term: Maximum ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) depression (negative deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the depression of the ST segment. (NCI)
term: Mean ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum depression (negative deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the depression of the ST segment. (NCI)
term: Minimum ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the ST segment depression below the isoelectric baseline measured from the baseline to the ST segment of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate ST segment deviation value based on the measurement of ST segment deviation from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum deviation (distance from baseline, positive or negative, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the deviation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) deviation (distance from baseline, positive or negative, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the deviation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum deviation (distance from baseline, positive or negative, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the deviation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the ST segment deviation above or below the isoelectric baseline measured from the baseline to the ST segment of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate ST segment elevation value based on the measurement of ST segment elevation from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The maximum elevation (positive deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the elevation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) elevation (positive deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the elevation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The minimum elevation (positive deflection from baseline, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the elevation of the ST segment. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the ST segment elevation above the isoelectric baseline measured from the baseline to the ST segment of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate ST segment duration value based on the measurement of ST segment duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the J point to the onset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the ST segment, measured from the J point at the end of the QRS complex to the beginning of the T wave.

name: ECG Test Code
synonym: ST Segment, T wave, and U wave
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of the characteristics of the ST segment, T wave, and U wave.
term: ST Segment, T wave, and U wave ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate S wave amplitude value based on the measurement of S wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the S wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the S wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) amplitude (usually in mm) of the S wave, obtained from a set of measurements of the S wave, in a particular lead or set of leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A statement about an electrocardiographic recording describing technical issues or interference during the recording, processing, or transmission of the data. This does not represent an electrocardiographic diagnosis.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate Tpeak-Tend value based on the measurement of Tpeak-Tend from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the peak of the T wave to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.
term: T Peak-T End Interval Single Beat

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate T wave area value based on the measurement of T wave areas from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the area of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) area under the curve of the deflection from baseline of the T wave (representing ventricular repolarization), obtained from a set of measurements of the T wave, from a single lead or set of leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) from the onset of ventricular repolarization to the completion of ventricular repolarization (length of the T wave), obtained from a set of measurements of the time from beginning to end of ventricular repolarization. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: The average (mean) height (usually measured in mm) of the maximum deflection from baseline of the T wave (representing ventricular repolarization), obtained from a set of measurements of the T wave, from a single lead or set of leads. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate T wave duration value based on the measurement of T wave duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the T wave to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An aggregate T wave amplitude value based on the measurement of T wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the T wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the T wave from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of ventricular arrhythmias excluding tachycardias.

name: ECG Test Code
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of supraventricular tachyarrhythmias.

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram lead placement on the subject using a ten electrode lead set to synthesize standard 12 lead electrocardiograph data to elicit an electrical view of the heart.

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but one standard lead position is missing therefore requiring a Mortara source consistency filter. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the display of the 12 standard ECG leads is in an orderly sequence in a single horizontal display of: aVL, I, -aVR, II, aVF, III, V1 to V6. In the Cabrera display the limb lead aVR is inverted (-aVR) to obtain the same positive leftward orientation as the other 5 limbs. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 4 chest electrodes and 1 reference electrode are used to allow for continuous monitoring at the clinical level. This placement creates a 12 lead ECG that allows the acquisition of simultaneous events in the frontal, horizontal and sagittal heart planes with the linear transformation of vectors. This system provides a three-dimensional portrayal of the heart and uses mathematical and fixed coefficients for each lead. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the standard lead positions have been modified for ECG recording during exercise. Exercise stress testing requires moving the limb electrodes to more central positions on the thorax. The electrodes are placed in bony prominences close to the bases of the respective limbs in order to avoid skeletal muscle artifact, provide stability for recording electrodes and to record waveforms similar to the standard limb sites. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the Mason Likar lead positions have been modified so that V1 to V6 on the chest are part of a single electrode pad. In addition, lead CM5 is substituted for lead aVR. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the limb leads are placed on the torso for easier and faster application in emergency situations. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
synonym: 12 Lead Right-sided Precordial Leads; Right-sided Chest Leads
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the precordial leads are intentionally placed on the right side of the chest.

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the standard lead positions have been modified so that all leads on the chest are part of a single electrode pad. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leads are recorded, with each lead representing an electrical view of the heart. The six leads recorded in the frontal plane are derived from the placement of 3 electrodes (RA or Right Arm, LA, or Left Arm, and LL or Left Leg). These bipolar frontal leads form the basis of Einthoven's triangle, and are represented by leads I, II, and III. Three other derived (or augmented) bipolar frontal vectors are also recorded on a standard 12-lead EKG, aVR, aVF, and aVL. 6 unipolar leads, corresponding to V1 - V6 measure the electrical activity in the horizontal plane. The placement for the V leads is as follows: V1: right 4th intercostal space,V2: left 4th intercostal space, V3: halfway between V2 and V4, V4: left 5th intercostal space, mid-clavicular line, V5: horizontal to V4, anterior axillary line, V6: horizontal to V5, mid-axillary line. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the position of the leads is unspecified. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram lead placement on the subject using a six electrode lead set with three standard leads and three augmented derived leads to elicit an electrical view of the heart.

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the X+ lead is placed at the right mid-axillary line ate the 4th intercostal space, X- at the left mid-axillary line at he 4th intercostal space, Y+ at the proximal left leg, Y- at the superior aspect of the manubrium, Z+ at the direct posterior to Z- and Z- at the 4th intercostal space at the left sternal margin. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement that is a type of uncorrected vectorcardiograph. This lead system is based on a rectangular body axis. It uses an extra number of electrodes to make it three-dimensional. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement for determining 3 orthogonal components X (right to left direction), Y (foot to head direction) and Z (back to front direction) of the heart. For this method a minimum of 4 electrodes are needed that represent the right arm, left arm, left leg and back. However, usually 7 electrodes are used to avoid dependence on the dipole location and facilitate interpretation. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement for determining 3 orthogonal components X (back to front), Y (right to left) and Z (foot to head) of the heart. This system places the electrodes closer to the heart to achieve better orthogonality and a homogeneous lead field. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement that allows monitoring and recording of cardiac electrical activity. A V1-type lead is used whose positive electrode is localized in the 4th intercostal space, 2.5cm from the sternum. Its negative electrode is placed below the left clavicle. An addition of lead V5 and aVF can be made to facilitate interpretation. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the standard lead positions have been modified so that the negative reference is at CM5 and the active electrode is at the left leg position. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby 12 leadpoints are recorded but the standard lead positions have been modified so that the bipolar lead groups place the negative of the reference electrode over the manubrium (CM5), the right scapula (CB5), V5R (CC5) or on the forehead (CH5) and the active electrode at V5. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
synonym: Standard 12-lead extended to the left by V7, V8, V9
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the standard lead placement is modified by having leads V7, V8 and V9. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
synonym: Standard 12-lead extended to the right by V5R, V4R, V3R
definition: An electrocardiogram (ECG) lead placement whereby the rightward oriented V leads progress from V1R, placed instead of the standard V2, to V6R. The V3 lead in the standard placement is replaced by V4R. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
synonym: Standard leads for bicycle exercise. Limb leads on the back (shoulder and on the hips)
definition: Limb leads on the back (shoulder and on the hips). (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
value: STANDARD LEADS ONE INTERCOSTAL SPACE HIGHER
synonym: Standard leads one intercostal space higher
definition: An electrocardiographic lead placement schema in which the V leads are placed one intercostal space cephalad to the position they would have in the standard lead placement schema. (NCI)
term: Lead Placement Standard Intercostal Space Higher

name: ECG Test Method
definition: A recording of the electrical activity of the heart displayed in the form of a vector loop, corrected for anatomic inconsistencies. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Method
definition: A recording of the electrical activity of the heart displayed in the form of a vector loop, uncorrected for anatomic inconsistencies. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic finding assessment of new or presumed new significant ST-segment-T wave (ST-T) changes or new left bundle branch block consistent with acute myocardial ischemia. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012)
term: Acute Myocardial Ischemia by ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of cardiac atrioventricular conduction.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of mean cardiac electrical vector and the ECG voltage.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of chamber hypertrophy or enlargement.
term: Chamber Hypertrophy or Enlargement ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A comparative interpretation of an ECG relative to a previous (comparator) ECG. The definition of the comparator ECG may be specified elsewhere. Common comparator result values include improved, no change, deteriorated.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the maximum ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the mean ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the average rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the median rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the median rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of depolarization of a specific region of the heart during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute. Unless otherwise specified, this is usually the minimum ventricular rate.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of ventricular depolarizations (QRS complexes) recorded during an interval of time, usually expressed in beats per minute.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An act or process of elucidation; explication, or explanation of the meaning of the event or thing via the assignment of objects from the domain to the constants of a formal language, truth-values to the proposition symbols, truth-functions to the connectives, other functions to the function symbols, and extensions to the predicates, if any. The assignments are result of human logic application and are not native to the symbols of the formal language.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of intraventricular and intra-atrial conduction.
term: Intraventricular and Intraatrial Conduction ECG Assessment

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate J-Tpeak value based on the measurement of J-Tpeak intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the J point to the peak of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate JT value based on the measurement of JT intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the J point to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A JTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A JTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A JTAG interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A JTSB interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: JTcB = JT/SqRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the JT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. It is mathematically defined as: JTcF = JT/CubeRootRR(seconds) and theoretically corrects the JT interval to that which would be observed at a heart rate of 1 cycle per second. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A formula which takes into account the physiologic shortening of the JT interval which occurs as the heart rate increases, permitting comparison of the JT interval across a range of rates. The linear correction formula uses population-based data obtained and validated using a large cohort of subjects. Using this method, the corrected JT interval is independent of the ventricular rate. (NCI)

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of findings suggestive of myocardial infarction.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic finding assessment of new or presumed new pathologic Q waves suggestive of myocardial infarction. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012).

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate P wave amplitude value based on the measurement of P wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the P wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the P wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the P wave from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate P wave duration value based on the measurement of P wave duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the P wave to the offset of the P wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate PP value based on the measurement of PP intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the interval between the onsets of two consecutive P waves.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate PR value based on the measurement of PR intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the P wave to the onset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic assessment of presence of artificial electronic pacing.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate Q wave amplitude value based on the measurement of Q wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the Q wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the Q wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the QRS complex from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: The average (mean) duration (time) of the QRS interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QRS interval while the ventricle rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from a mechanical cardiac pacemaker. The QRS interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the QRS complex, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate QRS value based on the measurement of QRS intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the QRS complex to the offset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate paced QRS duration value based on the measurement of paced QRS duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.

name: ECG Test Name
value: QRS Duration, Ventr. Paced, Single Beat
synonym: QRS Duration, Ventr. Paced, Single Beat
definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the paced QRS complex to the offset of the QRS complex of a single beat utilizing one or more leads.
term: Paced Ventricular Single Beat QRS Duration

name: ECG Test Name
definition: An aggregate QT value based on the measurement of QT intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean.
