name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A product that is packaged under pressure and contains therapeutically active ingredients that are released upon activation of an appropriate valve system; it is intended for topical application to the skin as well as local application into the nose (nasal aerosols), mouth (lingual aerosols), or lungs (inhalation aerosols).

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form containing one or more active ingredients, surfactants, aqueous or non-aqueous liquids, and the propellants; if the propellant is in the internal (discontinuous) phase (i.e., of the oil-in-water type), a stable foam is discharged, and if the propellant is in the external (continuous) phase (i.e., of the water-in-oil type), a spray or a quick-breaking foam is discharged.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A pressurized dosage form consisting of metered dose valves which allow for the delivery of a uniform quantity of spray upon each activation. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A product that is packaged under pressure and contains therapeutically active ingredients, in the form of a powder, that are released upon activation of an appropriate valve system. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An aerosol product which utilizes a compressed gas as the propellant to provide the force necessary to expel the product as a wet spray; it is applicable to solutions of medicinal agents in aqueous solvents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form usually in the form of a rectangle that is meant to be chewed. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in the shape of a small ball. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small sterile solid mass consisting of a highly purified drug intended for implantation in the body which would allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)
term: Extended Release Bead Implant Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Solid dosage form, usually in the shape of a square or rectangle. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which a tablet has been compacted into capsule shape.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid pharmaceutical dosage form that contains medicinal agent within either a hard or soft soluble container or shell, usually used for the oral administration of medicine. The shells are made of a suitable form of gelatin or other substance. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container or "shell" made from a suitable form of gelatin; additionally, the capsule is covered in a designated coating.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container or 'shell' made from a suitable form of gelatin; the drug itself is in the form of granules to which varying amounts of coating have been applied. (NCI)
term: Coated Pellet in Capsule Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container or "shell" made from a suitable form of gelatin; additionally, the capsule is covered in a designated coating, and which releases a drug (or drugs) in such a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form.
term: Extended Release Coated Capsule Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container made from a suitable form of gelatin, and which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. Enteric-coated articles are delayed release dosage forms. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container or "shell" made from a suitable form of gelatin; the drug itself is in the form of granules to which enteric coating has been applied, thus delaying release of the drug until its passage into the intestines.
term: Delayed Release Pellet in Capsule Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container made from a suitable form of gelatin, and which releases a drug (or drugs) in such a manner to allow a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container or 'shell' made from a suitable form of gelatin; additionally, the capsule is covered in a designated film coating, and which releases a drug (or drugs) in such a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form.
term: Extended Release Film Coated Capsule Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within either a hard or soft soluble container made from a suitable form of gelatin; through a banding process, the capsule is coated with additional layers of gelatin so as to form a complete seal. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug is enclosed within a soluble, gelatin shell which is plasticized by the addition of a polyol, such as sorbitol or glycerin, and is therefore of a somewhat thicker consistency than that of a hard shell capsule; typically, the active ingredients are dissolved or suspended in a liquid vehicle. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A substance that serves to produce solid union between two surfaces. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A narrow tube filled with material that is capable to burn with release of therapeutically-active substance(s) during the process of smoking. Cigarette is a very efficient drug-delivery inhaler system for fast-acting substances.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A large piece of relatively flat, absorbent material that contains a drug. It is typically used for applying medication or for cleansing.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation of increased strength and reduced volume which is usually diluted prior to administration. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form bounded by a circular base and the surface formed by line segments joining every point of the boundary of the base to a common vertex. A cone (usually containing antibiotics) is normally placed below the gingiva after a dental extraction. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An ocular system placed in the eye from which the drug diffuses through a membrane at a constant rate over a specified period. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A semisolid emulsion of either the oil-in-water or the water-in-oil type, ordinarily intended for topical use. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A cream dosage form that enhances drug delivery. Augmentation does not refer to the strength of the drug in the dosage form. NOTE: CDER has decided to refrain from expanding the use of this dosage form due to difficulties in setting specific criteria that must be met to be considered augmented.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A naturally produced angular solid of definite form in which the ultimate units from which it is built up are systematically arranged; they are usually evenly spaced on a regular space lattice.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: The propagation of microorganisms or of living tissue cells in special media conducive to their growth. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A device usually dome-shaped, worn during copulation over the cervical mouth for prevention of conception or infection. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A circular plate-like organ or structure.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation, intended for the irrigative cleansing of the vagina, that is prepared from powders, liquid solutions, or liquid concentrates and contains one or more chemical substances dissolved in a suitable solvent or mutually miscible solvents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: The application of various materials for protecting a wound.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Modern technology, distributed with or as a part of a drug product that allows for the uniform release or targeting of drugs to the body.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A clear, pleasantly flavored, sweetened hydroalcoholic liquid containing dissolved medicinal agents; it is intended for oral use. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form consisting of a two-phase system comprised of at least two immiscible liquids (1), one of which is dispersed as droplets (internal or dispersed phase) within the other liquid (external or continuous phase), generally stabilized with one or more emulsifying agents. Note 1: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior. Note 2: Emulsion is used as a dosage form term unless a more specific term is applicable, e.g. cream, lotion, ointment. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A rectal preparation for therapeutic, diagnostic, or nutritive purposes. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A concentrated preparation of vegetable or animal drugs obtained by removal of the active constituents of the respective drugs with a suitable menstrua, evaporation of all or nearly all of the solvent, and adjustment of the residual masses or powders to the prescribed standards. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A slender and elongated solid thread-like substance that delivers drug in such a manner to allow a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A thin layer or coating. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a film that releases the drug over an extended period in such a way as to maintain constant drug levels in the blood or target tissue. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A thin layer or coating which is susceptible to being dissolved when in contact with a liquid. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A product, usually a solid, intended for solution prior to administration.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A product, usually a solid, intended for suspension prior to administration.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A product, usually a solid, intended for suspension prior to administration; once the suspension is administered, the drug will be released at a constant rate over a specified period.
term: Extended Release Dosage Form for Suspension

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Any elastic aeriform fluid in which the molecules are separated from one another and have free paths. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A semisolid (1) dosage form that contains a gelling agent to provide stiffness to a solution or a colloidal dispersion (2). A gel may contain suspended particles. Note 1: A semisolid is not pourable; it does not flow or conform to its container at room temperature. It does not flow at low shear stress and generally exhibits plastic flow behavior. Note 2: A colloidal dispersion is a system in which particles of colloidal dimension (i.e., typically between 1 nm and 1 micrometer) are distributed uniformly throughout a liquid.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A combination of a dentifrice (formulation intended to clean and/or polish the teeth, and which may contain certain additional agents), and a gel. It is used with a toothbrush for the purpose of cleaning and polishing the teeth. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A gel preparation, with metered dose valves, which allow for the delivery of a uniform quantity of gel upon each activation.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An apparatus for the formation of vapor or gas from a liquid or solid by heat or chemical action. The term GENERATOR also applies to radioactive columns from which radionuclides are provided. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Also called pellets or pilules, are made of pure sucrose, lactose, or other polysaccharides. They are formed into small globular masses of various sizes, and are medicated by placing them in a vial and adding the liquid drug attenuation in the proportion not less than one percent (v/w). After shaking, the medicated globules are dried at temperatures not to exceed 40 degrees Centigrade. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A slip of skin or of other tissue for implantation. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small particle or grain. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small medicinal particle or grain to which an enteric or other coating has been applied, thus delaying release of the drug until its passage into the intestines. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small particle or grain containing a medicinal agent in a dry mixture usually composed of sodium bicarbonate, citric acid, and tartaric acid which, when in contact with water, has the capability to release gas, resulting in effervescence. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small medicinal particle or grain made available in its more stable dry form, to be reconstituted with solvent just before dispensing; the granules are so prepared to contain not only the medicinal agent, but the colorants, flavorants, and any other desired pharmaceutic ingredient. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small medicinal particle or grain made available in its more stable dry form, to be reconstituted with solvent just before dispensing to form a suspension; the granules are so prepared to contain not only the medicinal agent, but the colorants, flavorants, and any other desired pharmaceutic ingredient. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small medicinal particle or grain made available in its more stable dry form, to be reconstituted with solvent just before dispensing to form a suspension; the extended release system achieves slow release of the drug over an extended period of time and maintains constant drug levels in the blood or target tissue. (NCI)
term: Extended Release Granule for Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A mucilaginous excretion from various plants. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sweetened and flavored insoluble plastic material of various shapes which when chewed, releases a drug substance into the oral cavity. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Natural mixture of gum and resin, usually obtained as exudations from plants. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A material containing drug intended to be inserted securely and deeply in a living site for growth, slow release, or formation of an organic union. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A special class of inhalations consisting of a drug or combination of drugs, that by virtue of their high vapor pressure, can be carried by an air current into the nasal passage where they exert their effect; the container from which the inhalant generally is administered is known as an inhaler. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An injection, which either consists of or forms liposomes (a lipid bilayer vesicle usually composed of phospholipids which is used to encapsulate an active drug substance).

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile preparation intended for parenteral use; five distinct classes of injections exist as defined by the USP. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An emulsion consisting of a sterile, pyrogen-free preparation intended to be administered parenterally.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: [definition pending]

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile preparation intended for reconstitution to form a solution for parenteral use. (NCI)
term: Powder for Injectable Solution Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile preparation intended for reconstitution to form a suspension for parenteral use. (NCI)
term: Powder for Injectable Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
value: INJECTION, POWDER, FOR SUSPENSION, EXTENDED RELEASE
definition: A dried preparation intended for reconstitution to form a suspension for parenteral use which has been formulated in a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., as a solution).
term: Powder for Injectable Extended Release Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
value: INJECTION, POWDER, LYOPHILIZED, FOR LIPOSOMAL SUSPENSION
definition: A sterile freeze dried preparation intended for reconstitution for parenteral use which has been formulated in a manner that would allow liposomes (a lipid bilayer vesicle usually composed of phospholipids which is used to encapsulate an active drug substance, either within a lipid bilayer or in an aqueous space) to be formed upon reconstitution. (NCI)
term: Lyophilized Powder for Injectable Liposomal Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form intended for the solution prepared by lyophilization ('freeze drying'), a process which involves the removal of water from products in the frozen state at extremely low pressures; this is intended for subsequent addition of liquid to create a solution that conforms in all respects to the requirements for Injections. (NCI)
term: Lyophilized Powder for Injectable Solution Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation, intended for parenteral use, that contains solids suspended in a suitable fluid medium and conforms in all respects to the requirements for Sterile Suspensions; the medicinal agents intended for the suspension are prepared by lyophilization ("freeze drying"), a process which involves the removal of water from products in the frozen state at extremely low pressures.
term: Lyophilized Powder for Injectable Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
value: INJECTION, POWDER, LYOPHILIZED, FOR SUSPENSION, EXTENDED RELEASE
definition: A sterile freeze dried preparation intended for reconstitution for parenteral use which has been formulated in a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., as a solution). (NCI)
term: Lyophilized Powder for Extended Release Injectable Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation containing one or more drug substances dissolved in a suitable solvent or mixture of mutually miscible solvents that is suitable for injection. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile preparation for parenteral use which, upon the addition of suitable solvents, yields a solution conforming in all respects to the requirements for Injections. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation, suitable for injection, which consists of solid particles dispersed throughout a liquid phase in which the particles are not soluble. It can also consist of an oil phase dispersed throughout an aqueous phase, or vice-versa. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile preparation intended for parenteral use which has been formulated in a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., as a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)
term: Injectable Extended Release Suspension Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid parenteral pharmaceutical dosage form structured as a multilamellar composition of concentric phospholipid spheres that encapsulate the drug (drug delivery systems) separated by layers of water. Drug release is facilitated and controlled by in vivo erosion of the liposomes. To further increase the in vivo circulation time, liposomes in some preparations are covalently derivatized with PEG to produce PEGylated or stealth liposomes. Covalent attachment of drugs to the outer surface of liposomes can potentially serve as a delayed-release product. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation, suitable for injection, which consists of solid particles dispersed throughout a liquid phase in which the particles are not soluble. In addition, the product is sonicated while a gas is bubbled through the suspension, and this results in the formation of microspheres by the solid particles. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A specially formulated and shaped non-encapsulated solid preparation intended to be placed into a non-rectal orifice of the body, where drug is released, generally for localized effects.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A specially formulated and shaped solid preparation (e.g., ring, tablet, or stick) intended to be placed in the vagina by special inserters, where the medication is released, generally for localized effects; the extended release preparation is designed to allow a reduction in dosing frequency. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A device inserted and left in the uterus to prevent effective conception. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A sterile solution intended to bathe or flush open wounds or body cavities; they're used topically, never parenterally. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A class of gels--semisolid systems which consist of suspensions made up of either small inorganic particles or large organic molecules interpenetrated by a liquid--in which the structural coherent matrix contains a high portion of liquid, usually water. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A packaged collection of related material. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A material applied to the inside of the dental cavity, for protection or insulation of the surface.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solution or mixture of various substances in oil, alcoholic solutions of soap, or emulsions intended for external application. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A waxy solid, usually colored cosmetic, in stick form for the lips. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form consisting of a pure chemical in its liquid state. This dosage form term should not be applied to solutions. Note: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid that delivers a drug in such a manner to allow a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An emulsion, liquid (1) dosage form. This dosage form is generally for external application to the skin (2). Note 1: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior. Note 2: Previously the definition of a lotion was: The term lotion has been used to categorize many topical suspensions, solutions, and emulsions intended for application to the skin. The current definition of a lotion is restricted to an emulsion.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A lotion dosage form that enhances drug delivery. Augmentation does not refer to the strength of the drug in the dosage form. NOTE: CDER has decided to refrain from expanding the use of this dosage form due to difficulties in setting specific criteria that must be met to be considered augmented.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A lotion dosage form which has a soap or detergent that is usually used to clean the hair and scalp; it is often used as a vehicle for dermatologic agents.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid preparation containing one or more medicaments, usually in a flavored, sweetened base which is intended to dissolve or disintegrate slowly in the mouth. A lollipop is a lozenge on a stick.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An aqueous solution which is most often used for its deodorant, refreshing, or antiseptic effect. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: The use of a dosage form term is not relevant or appropriate. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An unctuous, combustible substance which is liquid, or easily liquefiable, on warming, and is soluble in ether but insoluble in water. Such substances, depending on their origin, are classified as animal, mineral, or vegetable oils. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A suspension or emulsion, semisolid (1) dosage form, usually containing < 20% water and volatiles (2) and > 50% hydrocarbons, waxes, or polyols as the vehicle. This dosage form is generally for external application to the skin or mucous membranes. Note 1: A semisolid is not pourable; it does not flow or conform to its container at room temperature. It does not flow at low shear stress and generally exhibits plastic flow behavior. Note 2: Percent water and volatiles are measured by a loss on drying test in which the sample is heated at 105 degrees C until constant weight is achieved.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An ointment dosage form that enhances drug delivery. Augmentation does not refer to the strength of the drug in the dosage form. NOTE: CDER has decided to refrain from expanding the use of this dosage form due to difficulties in setting specific criteria that must be met to be considered augmented.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A material, usually covered by or impregnated with a drug, that is inserted into a body cavity or between the tooth enamel and the gingival margin.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A semisolid dosage form, containing a large proportion (20 - 50%) of solids finely dispersed in a fatty vehicle. This dosage form is generally for external application to the skin or mucous membranes. Note: A semisolid is not pourable; it does not flow or conform to its container at room temperature. It does not flow at low shear stress and generally exhibits plastic flow behavior. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A paste formulation intended to clean and/or polish the teeth, and which may contain certain additional agents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An aromatic preparation, often with a pleasing flavor, usually intended to dissolve in the mouth.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system that often contains an adhesive backing that is usually applied to an external site on the body. Its ingredients either passively diffuse from, or are actively transported from, some portion of the patch. Depending upon the patch, the ingredients are either delivered to the outer surface of the body or into the body. A patch is sometimes synonymous with the terms Extended Release Film and System.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a patch that releases the drug in such a manner that a reduction in dosing frequency compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a patch which is controlled by an electric current that releases the drug in such a manner that a reduction in dosing frequency compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)
term: Electrically Controlled Extended Release Patch Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small sterile solid mass consisting of a highly purified drug (with or without excipients) made by the formation of granules, or by compression and molding. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small sterile solid mass consisting of a highly purified drug (with or without excipients) made by the formation of granules, or by compression and molding; they are intended for implantation in the body (usually subcutaneously) for the purpose of providing continuous release of the drug over long periods of time.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug itself is in the form of granules to which varying amounts of coating have been applied, and which releases a drug (or drugs) in such a manner to allow a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)
term: Extended Release Coated Pellet Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dose of medicine in the form of a small pellet. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Substance intended for external application made of such materials and of such consistency as to adhere to the skin and attach to a dressing; plasters are intended to afford protection and support and/or to furnish an occlusion and macerating action and to bring medication into close contact with the skin.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A soft, moist mass of meal, herbs, seed, etc., usually applied hot in cloth that consists of gruel-like consistency. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals that may be intended for internal or external use. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A powder formulation intended to clean and/or polish the teeth, and which may contain certain additional agents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals, which, upon the addition of suitable vehicles, yields a solution. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals, which, upon the addition of suitable vehicles, yields a suspension (a liquid preparation containing the solid particles dispersed in the liquid vehicle). (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A powder dosage form that is situated inside a container that has a mechanism to deliver a specified quantity. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small circular object with a vacant circular center that is usually intended to be placed in the body by special inserters, where the medication is released, generally for localized effects.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid used to cleanse by flushing. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A thick ointment or cerate (a fat or wax based preparation with a consistency between an ointment and a plaster). (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid soap or detergent used to clean the hair and scalp and is often used as a vehicle for dermatologic agents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid soap or detergent containing one or more solid, insoluble substances dispersed in a liquid vehicle that is used to clean the hair and scalp and is often used as a vehicle for dermatologic agents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: Any compound of one or more fatty acids, or their equivalents, with an alkali; soap is detergent and is much employed in liniments, enemas, and in making pills. It is also a mild aperient, antacid and antiseptic. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A clear, homogeneous liquid dosage form that contains one or more chemical substances dissolved in a solvent or mixture of mutually miscible solvents. Note: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation (i.e., a substance that flows readily in its natural state) that contains a drug dissolved in a suitable solvent or mixture of mutually miscible solvents; the drug has been strengthened by the evaporation of its non-active parts. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solution for the preparation of an iced saline slush, which is administered by irrigation and used to induce regional hypothermia (in conditions such as certain open heart and kidney surgical procedures) by its direct application. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solution, which after usually being administered in a drop-wise fashion, forms a gel.
term: Gel Forming Drop Solution Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solution that forms a gel when it comes in contact with ocular fluid, and which allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency.
term: Extended Release Gel Forming Solution Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solution which is usually administered in a drop-wise fashion.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A porous, interlacing, absorbent material that contains a drug. It is typically used for applying or introducing medication, or for cleansing. A sponge usually retains its shape.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid minutely divided as by a jet of air or steam. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A non-pressurized dosage form consisting of valves which allow the dispensing of a specified quantity of spray upon each activation. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation containing solid particles dispersed in a liquid vehicle and in the form of coarse droplets or as finely divided solids to be applied locally, most usually to the nasal-pharyngeal tract, or topically to the skin. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form prepared in a relatively long and slender often cylindrical form. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A long narrow piece of material.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid body of various weights and shapes, adapted for introduction into the rectal, vaginal, or urethral orifice of the human body; they usually melt, soften, or dissolve at body temperature.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a suppository that allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid dosage form that contains solid particles dispersed in a liquid vehicle. Note: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation consisting of solid particles dispersed throughout a liquid phase in which the particles are not soluble; the suspension has been formulated in a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., as a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A suspension which is usually administered in a dropwise fashion.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A strand or fiber used to hold wound edges in apposition during healing. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A small piece of relatively flat absorbent material that contains a drug. A swab may also be attached to one end of a small stick. A swab is typically used for applying medication or for cleansing.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: An oral solution containing high concentrations of sucrose or other sugars; the term has also been used to include any other liquid dosage form prepared in a sweet and viscid vehicle, including oral suspensions. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents that is intended to be chewed, producing a pleasant tasting residue in the oral cavity that is easily swallowed and does not leave a bitter or unpleasant after-taste. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is covered with a designated coating. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a conglomerate of medicinal particles that have each been covered with a coating.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. Enteric-coated articles are delayed release dosage forms. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a conglomerate of medicinal particles that have been covered with a coating which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. Enteric-coated articles are delayed release dosage forms. (NCI)
term: Delayed Release Particle Tablet Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing mixtures of acids (e.g., citric acid, tartaric acid) and sodium bicarbonate, which release carbon dioxide when dissolved in water; it is intended to be dissolved or dispersed in water before administration.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a drug which allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented in conventional dosage form. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a thin layer of a water-insoluble or water-soluble polymer. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a thin layer of a water-insoluble or water-soluble polymer; the tablet is formulated in such manner as to make the contained medicament available over an extended period of time following ingestion.
term: Film Coated Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A tablet that forms a solution when placed in a liquid.

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A tablet that forms a suspension when placed in a liquid (formerly referred to as a Dispersible Tablet).

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances that have been compressed to form a multiple-layered tablet or a tablet-within-a-tablet, the inner tablet being the core and the outer portion being the shell. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances that have been compressed to form a multiple-layered tablet or a tablet-within-a-tablet, the inner tablet being the core and the outer portion being the shell, which, additionally, is covered in a designated coating; the tablet is formulated in such manner as to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)
term: Multilayered Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances which disintegrates rapidly, usually within a matter of seconds, when placed upon the tongue. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances which disintegrates rapidly, usually within a matter of seconds, when placed upon the tongue, but which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration.
term: Orally Disintegrating Delayed Release Tablet Dosage Form

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and possesses the ability to dissolve in fluids. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a colored or an uncolored water-soluble sugar. (NCI)

name: Pharmaceutical Dosage Form

For the sake of simplicity, this definition applies to the extracranial carotid artery and other non-cardiac arteries and veins, while it excludes the lymphatics and intracranial vessels.

name: Procedure Urgency Status

name: Procedure Urgency Status
definition: Performing a salvage procedure is the last resort. The clinical situation involves either ongoing life support measures, life support measures for more than 60 seconds during the prior 10 minutes, or unanticipated institution of extracorporeal circulatory support.

name: Procedure Urgency Status
definition: Deferring an urgent procedure increases risk of adverse outcome or clinical deterioration. Clinical situation warrants performing urgent procedures during the current episode of care to avoid compromising patient safety.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Datasets used for statistical analysis and reporting by the sponsor. These are submitted in addition to the data tabulation datasets.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Adverse events may be captured either as free text or a pre-specified list of terms.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for the agents administered to the subject as part of a procedure or assessment as opposed to drugs, medications and therapies administered with therapeutic intent.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Additional data about deaths, specific to findings from autopsies.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Prefix to indicate an analysis dataset that is not compliant with a defined ADaM structure.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: An events domain that documents biospecimen collection and storage information.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings resulting from evaluations of bone mineral density.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings resulting from biopsies.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A findings domain that documents biospecimen handling information.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A dataset used to capture clinical events of interest that would not be classified as adverse events.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Case report form (CRF) data that captures the Concomitant and Prior Medications/Therapies used by the subject. Examples are the Concomitant Medications/Therapies given on an as needed basis and the usual Background Medications/Therapies given for a condition.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The Comments dataset accommodates two sources of comments: 1) those collected alongside other data on topical case report form (CRF) pages such as Adverse Events and 2) those collected on a separate page specifically dedicated to comments.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the cardiovascular system, including the heart, blood vessels and lymphatic vessels.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Data regarding the accountability of study drug, such as information on the receipt, dispensing, return, and packaging.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This domain captures the diagnosis of the cause of death for a subject.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for device-related events.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for the submission of information that identifies a specific device unit.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The Demographics domain includes a set of essential standard variables that describe each subject in a clinical study. It is the parent domain for all other observations for human clinical subjects.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for the characteristics of the device that do not vary over the course of the study.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This domain captures the outcome of developmental milestone testing during a scheduled period of observation.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for the linkage of each subject to the device(s) to which they may have been exposed.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to disposition. (NCI)

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for logistics and disposition information specific to a given device.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for the findings for the values of measurements and settings that are intentionally set on a device when it is in use. These are characteristics that exist for the device, and have a specific setting for a use instance.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The intent of the domain is to capture protocol violations and deviations during the course of the study and will store only those criteria violation by or deviated from by the subject and not a response to each violation or deviation.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for a subject's exposure to a medical device under study.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the endocrine system, including the glands and cells that make hormones that are released directly into the blood and travel to tissues and organs all over the body.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings related to the collection of ECG data, including position of the subject, method of evaluation, all cycle measurements and all findings from the ECG including an overall interpretation if collected or derived.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The Exposure domain model records the details of a subject's exposure to protocol-specified study treatment. Study treatment may be any intervention that is prospectively defined as a test material within a study, and is typically but not always supplied to the subject.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A dataset used to capture the findings about an event or intervention that cannot be represented within an event or intervention record or as a supplemental qualifier.
term: Findings About Events or Interventions Domain

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to family history. (NCI)

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for named, stand-alone task-based evaluations designed to provide an assessment of mobility, dexterity, or cognitive ability.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the gastrointestinal system, including the esophagus, stomach, small and large intestine, anus, liver, biliary tract and pancreas.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the hematopoietic system, including the bone marrow and lymph nodes involved in the production of blood.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for inpatient and outpatient healthcare events.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Healthcare resource utilization data such as subject visits to physicians, hospitalizations, and nursing home stays.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The intent of the domain model is to only collect those criteria that cause the subject to be in violation of the inclusion/exclusion criteria not a response to each criterion.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the integumentary system, including the epidermis, dermis, all of the derivatives of the epidermis, hairs, nails, sudoriferous and sebaceous glands, and mammary glands.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the immune system, including the thymus, spleen and tonsils.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A findings domain for assessments that determine whether a therapy induced an immune response.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Laboratory test findings including, but is not limited to hematology, clinical chemistry and urinalysis data. This domain does not include microbiology or pharmacokinetic data, which are stored in separate domains.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Microbiology specimen findings, including gram stain results, and organisms found.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The medical history dataset includes the subject's prior history at the start of the trial. Examples of subject medical history information could include general medical history, gynecological history, and primary diagnosis.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The histopathology findings and microscopic evaluations recorded.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation

term: Musculoskeletal Findings, Connective and Soft Tissue Findings Domain

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Information regarding the subject's meal consumption, such as fluid intake, amounts, form (solid or liquid state), frequency, etc., typically used for pharmacokinetic analysis.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain relevant to the science of the form and structure of an organism or of its parts.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This includes microbiology susceptibility test results, plus results of any other organism-related tests.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the nervous system, including the brain, spinal cord, the cranial and spinal nerves, autonomic ganglia and plexuses.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A special-purpose domain that relates a set of genetic variations to an inference about the medical meaning of that set of genetic variations.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Concentrations of drugs/metabolites in fluids or tissues as a function of time.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings collected during a physical examination of the subject. It has findings that are discovered that are related to body systems. Does not include vital signs measurements, which are stored in the vital signs domain.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A findings domain for gene expression and genetic variation assessments.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Pharmacogenomics findings that initially focus on genotype and gene expression data.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Pharmacokinetic parameters derived from pharmacokinetic concentration-time (PC) data.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain relevant to an interventional activity that is intended to have diagnostic, preventive, therapeutic, or palliative effects.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A special purpose domain that contains the protocol summary information for pharmacogenomics assessments.
term: Protocol Summary for Pharmacogenomic Assessments Domain

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A special purpose domain that contains design parameters used in performing pharmacogenomic assessments.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Questionnaires are named, stand-alone instruments designed to provide an assessment of a concept. Questionnaires have a defined standard structure, format, and content; consist of conceptually related items that are typically scored; and have documented methods for administration and analysis. Most often, questionnaires have as their primary purpose the generation of a quantitative statistic to assess a qualitative concept.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the respiratory system, including the organs that are involved in breathing such as the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi and lungs.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the male and female reproductive systems.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The disease response (RS) domain represents disease response evaluations determined from collected data in the tumor results (TR) domain and/or other SDTM domains.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A special purpose domain that associates the subject with the medical conclusions contained in the pharmacogenomics biological state (PB) domain based on the observations reported in pharmacogenomics findings (PF) domain.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The subject characteristics domain is for data not collected in other domains that is subject-related.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The subject element table describes the actual order of elements followed by the subject, together with the start date/time and end date/time for each element.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Surgical information.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings from diagnostic skin tests.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Findings from diagnostic sleep tests (polysomnography).

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A findings about domain for submitting dermal responses to antigens.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The intent of the domain is to capture substance use information that may be used to assess the efficacy and/or safety of therapies that look to mitigate the effects of chronic substance use.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The subject visits table describes the actual start and end data/time for each visit of each individual subject.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial arms table describes each planned arm in the trial. An arm is described as an ordered sequence of elements.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial elements table describes the element code that is unique for each element, the element description, and the rules for starting and ending an element.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This domain captures the tumor findings of the nonclinical subject.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial summary information domain is not subject oriented. It contains one record for each of the inclusion and exclusion criteria for the trial.
term: Trial Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria Domain

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial paths domain is not subject oriented. This domain provides the complete planned non-treatment related sequences of stages for each path in a study.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This domain represents quantitative measurements and/or qualitative assessments of the tumors identified in the tumor identifier (TU) domain.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial summary information domain is not subject oriented. It contains one record for each trial summary characteristic.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: This domain represents data that uniquely identifies tumors.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial visits table describes the planned order and number of visits in the study within each arm.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: The trial stages domain is not subject oriented. It contains one record for each trial set characteristic including experimental factors, treatment factors, inherent characteristics, or distinct sponsor designations.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A domain for physiological findings related to the urinary tract, including the organs involved in the creation and excretion of urine such as the kidneys, ureters, bladder and urethra.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: A findings domain that contains information about virus drug-resistance.

name: SDTM Domain Abbreviation
definition: Measurements including but not limited to blood pressure, temperature, respiration, body surface area, BMI, height and weight.

name: Severity/Intensity Scale for Adverse Events
definition: A type of adverse event that is usually transient and may require only minimal treatment or therapeutic intervention. The event does not generally interfere with usual activities of daily living.

name: Severity/Intensity Scale for Adverse Events
definition: A type of adverse event that is usually alleviated with additional specific therapeutic intervention. The event interferes with usual activities of daily living, causing discomfort but poses no significant or permanent risk of harm to the research participant.

name: Severity/Intensity Scale for Adverse Events
definition: A type of adverse event that interrupts usual activities of daily living, or significantly affects clinical status, or may require intensive therapeutic intervention.

name: Sex
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces ova. The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, or cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

name: Sex
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces sperm. The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

name: Sex
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

name: Sex
definition: A person (one of unisexual specimens) who is born with genitalia and/or secondary sexual characteristics of indeterminate sex, or which combine features of both sexes. (NCI)

name: Sex of Participants

name: Sex of Participants

name: Sex of Participants
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces sperm. The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

name: Size
definition: Mid-way between small and large in number, quantity, magnitude or extent. (NCI)

name: Size

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who never tan and always sunburn if exposed to any appreciable amount of sunlight, primarily red headed individuals and lightly complected blondes. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who frequently burn but are able to tan to a small degree after extended sun exposure. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who burn infrequently and tan readily. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who rarely burn and tan heavily with moderate sun exposures, especially individuals of Asian, American Indian, Mediterranean and Latin American descent. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who have dark constitutive pigmentation but become noticeably darker with sun exposure, especially light complected black individuals, those of Indian descent. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Classification
definition: Individuals who have the heaviest constitutive pigmentation, especially dark skinned black individuals. (Reference: Fitzpatrick TB: The validity and practicality of sun-reactive skin types I through VI. Arch. Dermatol. 1998 124: 869-871)

name: Skin Response Test Code

name: Skin Response Test Code
definition: A semi-quantitative assessment of the intensity of the wheal and flare reaction.

name: Skin Response Test Code

name: Skin Type
definition: The pores are generally fine with a papery thin texture that feels dry to the touch. Usually flaky and dull looking.

name: Skin Type
definition: The pores are visible but not large. The texture is neither fine or thick and it neither feels dry or oily to the touch.

name: Skin Type
definition: The pores of the skin are generally large and visible with a coarse or thick texture. It has a tendency to look dull and greasy and feels oily to the touch.

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: An individual that came into contact with a source of Tuberculosis.
term: Subject in Contact With Tuberculosis Source

name: Social Risk Factor
value: CURRENT OR RECENT EMPLOYEE OR VOLUNTEER IN HOMELESS SHELTER
definition: An individual who is presently or not long ago worked or offered to assist without pay at a temporary housing facility for persons without a stable or permanent residence.
term: Current or Recent Employee or Volunteer in Homeless Shelter

name: Social Risk Factor
value: CURRENT OR RECENT EMPLOYEE OR VOLUNTEER IN JAIL OR PRISON
definition: An individual who is presently or not long ago worked or offered to assist without pay at an institution where persons are confined for punishment and to protect the public.
term: Current or Recent Employee or Volunteer in Jail or Prison

name: Social Risk Factor
value: CURRENT OR RECENT EMPLOYEE OR VOLUNTEER IN NURSING HOME
definition: An individual who is presently or not long ago worked or offered to assist without pay at a residential health care facility for persons with chronic illness or disability.
term: Current or Recent Employee or Volunteer in Nursing Home

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: An individual without a stable or permanent residence within the last 365 days.

name: Social Risk Factor
value: IMMIGRANT FROM HIGH TUBERCULOSIS PREVALENT AREA
definition: An individual that has migrated from a country with a high occurrence of tuberculosis.
term: Immigrant From High Tuberculosis Prevalent Area

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: The state of being confined to jail or prison.

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: An individual that resided in a camp for those displaced from their homeland.

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: An individual that lives at a healthcare facility that provides rehabilitative, restorative, and/or ongoing skilled nursing care to patients or residents in need of assistance with activities of daily living.

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: An individual who moves from one location to another location within or outside of their homeland for work.

name: Social Risk Factor
value: REFUGEE FROM HIGH TUBERCULOSIS PREVALENT AREA
definition: An individual that has fled a country for their own safety which has a high occurrence of tuberculosis.
term: Refugee From High Tuberculosis Prevalent Area

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: Entry into one or more of the 22 countries that have a relatively high prevalence of tuberculosis cases.
term: Travel To High Burden Tuberculosis Country

name: Social Risk Factor
definition: The state of not having a job.
