name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The watery fluid which is present in the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Oxygenated blood which is transported with nutrients to body tissues through the arterial system. The exception is blood within the pulmonary artery which carries deoxygenated blood to the lungs. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Blood present in the umbilical arteries at the time of delivery.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Fatty tissue which is deposited in the inner lining of the arterial wall. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Fluid composed of waste products, bile acids, salts, cholesterol, and electrolytes. It is secreted by the liver parenchyma and stored in the gallbladder. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A liquid tissue with the primary function of transporting oxygen and carbon dioxide. It supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Calcified connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The tissue occupying the spaces of bone. It consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells which give rise to the red cells, white cells, and megakaryocytes. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Milk produced by females for the purpose of feeding their young. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The middle fraction of an anticoagulated blood specimen following separation by centrifugation. It contains most of the white blood cells and platelets.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Accumulated material from the secretions of an organ. It is solid and representative examples include gallbladder stones, kidney stones, and salivary gland stones. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A mixture of arterial blood, venous blood and interstitial fluid, which is found in the capillaries.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid that is contained within the brain ventricles, the subarachnoid space and the central canal of the spinal cord. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A wax secreted by glands in the ear canal.

name: Specimen Type
definition: A metastatic cancer cell found in the peripheral blood. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A thick, protein-rich substance secreted by the breasts during the second half of pregnancy and for a few days after birth before the breast milk comes in.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Blood present in the umbilical vessels at the time of delivery.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins from the cord blood of a newborn baby.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid which runs through a dialysis machine and captures, for discard or analysis, the excess water and waste from the blood stream through diffusion and ultrafiltration. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Stomach contents that have returned to the mouth or are ejected beyond the mouth. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Cell specialized for oxygen transport, having a high concentration of hemoglobin in the cytoplasm and little else; biconcave, anucleate discs, 7nm diameter in mammals.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The air that moves out of the chest during expiration. It contains a higher percentage of carbon dioxide and a lower percentage of oxygen compared to the inhaled air. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Fluid, cells or cellular debris that escapes from the blood vessels and accumulates in nearby tissues. It is the result of inflammation and is rich in proteins.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Liquid substances produced by the body.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The contents of the stomach that may include undigested food mixed with juices secreted by the gastric mucosal glands. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which the sebaceous glands open; the follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The extracellular fluid component found in the spaces between tissues. This excludes plasma and transcellular fluid.

name: Specimen Type
definition: A specific individual microbe and its genetically identical progeny separated on a single occasion from a sample taken from a host or culture system.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Fluid introduced into, and collected from, a body cavity by lavage procedure. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Vaginal discharge occurring during the post-partum period. It consists of a mixture of blood, mucus, and placental remnants. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Pulmonary surfactant lines the lung epithelium and lowers surface tension to prevent collapse at end-expiration. Deficiency of pulmonary surfactant results in respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) in premature infants. Lung surfactant is synthesized in alveolar type II cells, stored in lamellar bodies and secreted via exocytosis. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A clear, transparent, sometimes faintly yellow and slightly opalescent fluid that is collected from the tissues throughout the body, flows in the lymphatic vessels (through the lymph nodes), and is eventually added to the venous blood circulation. Lymph consists of a clear liquid portion, varying numbers of white blood cells (chiefly lymphocytes), and a few red blood cells. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The cellular debris and fluid produced by lysis of cells.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The newborn's first intestinal discharge. It is a dark-green, thick substance composed of mucus, intestinal secretions, hair, and intestinal mucosa cells. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The discharged blood from the uterus during the reproductive years. The discharge occurs approximately once a month. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The thick fluid secreted by the mucus glands in the aerodigestive tract and the vagina. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A peripheral blood cell with a single nucleus, for example lymphocytes and monocytes.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid secreted by the sweat glands. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Plasma is the fluid (acellular) portion of the circulating blood, as distinguished from the serum that is the fluid portion of the blood obtained by removal of the fibrin clot and blood cells after coagulation.

name: Specimen Type
definition: An irregular, disc-shaped structure in the blood that assists in blood clotting. Platelets are not blood cells, they are fragments of large bone marrow cells called megakaryocytes. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to decrease the amount of platelets. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to concentrate the amount of platelets. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid that is abnormally collected in the pleural cavity. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A slightly alkaline, white fluid secreted from the prostate and is a constituent of semen.

name: Specimen Type
definition: A yellowish substance produced during bacterial inflammation. It contains necrotic cells and cells fighting the infection. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A clear liquid secreted into the mouth by the salivary glands and mucous glands of the mouth; moistens the mouth and starts the digestion of starches. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A thick, oily substance produced by the sebaceous glands located in the dermis. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The thick, whitish secretion of the male reproductive organs. It is composed of spermatozoa in their nutrient plasma, secretions from the prostate, seminal vesicles, and various other glands, epithelial cells, and minor constituents. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Part of the ejaculated fluid. It contains secretions from the seminal vesicles, Cowper gland, and prostate gland.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism. They are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A white secretion of the sebaceous glands of the foreskin. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. It is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. The smooth muscle cells contain a contractile apparatus composed of thin and thick filaments and a cytoskeleton composed of intermediate filaments. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Refers to muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, blood vessels or other supporting tissue of the body.

name: Specimen Type
definition: Material containing mucus, cellular debris, microorganisms and sometimes blood or pus. It is ejected through the mouth from the lungs, bronchi, and trachea. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The material discharged from the bowel during defecation. It consists of undigested food, intestinal mucus, epithelial cells, and bacteria. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Striated muscles are appendicular and axial muscles typically connected at either or both ends to the bony skeleton of the body. Striated muscle fibers contain a highly organized, contractile cytoskeletal apparatus with a striated microscopic appearance; muscle contraction is typically under voluntary control. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: An anatomical structure consisting of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships, performing a specific function. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid that passes through the wall of the veins and capillaries to the surrounding tissues because of increased intravascular pressure. It has low protein content. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: A tumor sample, or entire tumor that is removed for examination.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The fluid that is excreted by the kidneys. It is stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Deoxygenated blood containing urea and other waste products which is transported through the venous system to the heart and lungs. The exception is blood within the pulmonary vein which is oxygenated and travels from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart. (NCI)

name: Specimen Type
definition: Blood present in the umbilical vein at the time of delivery.

name: Specimen Type
definition: The clear colorless transparent jelly that fills the posterior chamber of the eyeball. (NCI)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary ARC Grade Responses
definition: Includes acute ischemic symptoms at rest, acute post ischemic ECG, positive biomarkers and pathological evidence. Definite stent thrombosis is considered to have occurred when there is either angiographic or pathological confirmation. Angiographic confirmation is the presence of a thrombus at coronary angiography that originates in the stent or in the segment 5 mm proximal or distal to the stent, with the presence of at least 1 of 3 clinical criteria within a 48-hour time window: 1) acute onset of ischemic symptoms at rest; 2) new ischemic ECG changes that suggest acute ischemia; or 3) typical rise and fall in cardiac biomarkers. Pathological confirmation is evidence of recent thrombus within the stent determined at autopsy or via examination of tissue retrieved following thrombectomy. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical End Points in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary ARC Grade Responses
definition: Possible stent thrombosis is considered to have occurred with any unexplained death more than 30 days after intracoronary stenting. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical End Points in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary ARC Grade Responses
definition: Includes death within 30 days and myocardial infarction of stent territory. Probable stent thrombosis is considered to have occurred after intracoronary stenting in the following situations: 1) any unexplained death within the first 30 days; or 2) irrespective of the time after the index procedure, any MI that is related to documented acute ischemia in the territory of the implanted stent without angiographic confirmation of stent thrombosis and in the absence of any other obvious cause. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical End Points in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary, ARC Timing Responses
definition: 0 to 24 hours after stent implantation. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical Endpoints in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary, ARC Timing Responses
definition: Greater than 30 days to 1 year after stent implantation. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical Endpoints in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary, ARC Timing Responses
definition: Greater than 24 hours to 30 days after stent implantation. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical Endpoints in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)

name: Stent Thrombosis, Coronary, ARC Timing Responses
definition: Greater than 1 year after stent implantation. (Cutlip DE, Windecker S, Mehran R, et al. Clinical Endpoints in Coronary Stent Trials : A Case for Standardized Definitions. Circulation. 2007;115:2344-2351)
term: ARC Stent Thrombosis Timing Very Late

name: Study Type
definition: Studies that provide a means for obtaining an experimental drug or device for patients who are not adequately treated by existing therapy, who do not meet the eligibility criteria for enrollment, or who are otherwise unable to participate in another clinical study. Expanded Access studies include individual-patient IND, treatment IND, compassionate use, emergency use or continued access.

name: Study Type
definition: Studies in which individuals are assigned by an investigator based on a protocol to receive specific interventions. Subjects may receive diagnostic, therapeutic or other types of interventions. The assignment of the intervention may or may not be random. The individuals are then followed and biomedical and/or health outcomes are assessed.

name: Study Type
definition: Studies in which biomedical and/or health outcomes are assessed in pre-defined groups of individuals. Subjects in the study may receive diagnostic, therapeutic, or other interventions, but the investigator does not assign specific interventions to the subjects of the study.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether the subject was breast fed (received mother's milk) as an infant.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A public health activity whereby individuals who have been exposed to a person with a suspected or confirmed contagious illness are identified, usually for the purpose of identifying additional cases of the illness, or to offer some form of prophylactic intervention to either prevent or ameliorate disease in the exposed individual.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
synonym: Entry Date from Ptntl Cntry Disease Exp
definition: The date on which the subject arrived in the reporting country from the country of potential disease exposure.
term: Entry Date from Country of Potential Disease Exposure

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: System of classification based on the nation in which an individual was exposed to a disease, regardless of the nation in which he/she currently resides.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: Years of education that a person has completed.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A code specifying the job performed by the employee for the employer. For example, accountant, programmer analyst, patient care associate, staff nurse, etc.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: The preferred hand of use for controlled and efficient performance of motor tasks.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A code qualifying the employment in various ways, such as, full-time vs. part time, etc.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A demographic parameter indicating a person's current conjugal status.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: System of classification based on nation from which a person originates, regardless of the nation in which he/she currently resides.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether the subject was born prior to 38 weeks gestation.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: The categorization of individuals with or without the potential for having a particular disease.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: An indication that a subject is part of a population group that has a greater chance of contracting a disease or disorder.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: Social factors such as personal behavior, lifestyle, or environment belonging to the subject which are known to increase the likelihood of infection and disease.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A code specifying the method used by the employer to compute the employee's salary or wages. For example, hourly, annual, or commission.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: The environment within which the person may have come into contact with a disease carrier, or played the role of a disease carrier.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A classification system used to categorize the sensitivity of a subject's skin to sunlight.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A distinctive characteristic of the skin marked by the amount of sebum secreted by sebaceous glands.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: A public health activity for the determination of who transmitted a disease to another subject and whether this person: is still infectious; was reported to the health department as a disease case or suspect; or has infected others.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: Subjective evidence of disease perceived by the patient.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: The classification of the two offspring born from the same pregnancy.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Code
definition: Identification and clinical investigation of disease contacts.

name: Subject Characteristic Test Name
definition: An indication as to whether the subject was breast fed (received mother's milk) as an infant.

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
synonym: Ventricular arrhythmia associated with Brugada syndrome
definition: Polymorphic ventricular tachycardia in the absence of structural heart disease, associated with a baseline ECG pattern during sinus rhythm showing right bundle branch block with ST segment elevation in leads V1 through V3. It can also be characterized by documentation of ECG patterns associated with Brugada Syndrome, some of which may be unmasked when provoked with drugs. The most common genetic mutations identified for Brugada syndrome are in the sodium channel gene SCN5A.
term: Brugada Syndrome Ventricular Arrhythmia by ECG Finding

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
definition: Ventricular Tachycardia associated with syncope and/or cardiac arrest triggered by emotion or exercise in patients whose baseline ECG is normal.
term: Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
definition: Ventricular tachycardia or ventricular fibrillation whose cause is unknown.
term: Idiopathic Primary Ventricular Tachycardia/Ventricular Flutter by ECG Finding

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
synonym: Ventricular arrhythmia associated with long QT syndrome
definition: Long QT Syndrome includes prolongation of the corrected QT interval beyond 440 ms for adult males, 460 ms for adult females and 50 ms in the presence of ventricular depolarization abnormalities (i.e., bundle branch blocks or IVCB more than 120 ms. A normal QT interval in a resting ECG with a failure to shorten with an increase in heart rate qualifies as Long QT Syndrome.

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
definition: Different than the one(s) previously specified or mentioned. (NCI)

name: Sudden Death Syndrome Type
synonym: Ventricular arrhythmia associated with short QT syndrome
definition: Short QT Syndrome is characterized by a QT interval of less than or equal to 300 ms.

name: Supporting Evidence for Re-Treatment
definition: Objective evidence of bacterial infection perceptible to the examiner by laboratory procedure.

name: Supporting Evidence for Re-Treatment
definition: Objective evidence of disease perceptible to the examiner (sign) and subjective evidence of disease perceived by the subject (symptom).

name: Supporting Evidence for Re-Treatment
definition: Objective evidence of disease perceptible to the examiner by radiological procedure.

name: TIMI Flow Responses
definition: No perfusion. There is no antegrade flow beyond the point of occlusion. (Chesebro JH, Knatterud GL, Roberts R, et al, Thrombolysis in Myocardial Infarction (TIMI) Trial, Phase I: a comparison between intravenous tissue plasminogen activator and intravenous streptokinase: Clinical findings through hospital discharge, Circulation 76, No. 1, 142-154, 1987)

name: TIMI Flow Responses
definition: Penetration without perfusion. Contrast material passes beyond the area of obstruction but "hangs up" and fails to opacify the entire coronary bed distal to the obstruction for the duration of the cineangiographic filming sequence. (Chesebro JH, Knatterud GL, Roberts R, et al, Thrombolysis in Myocardial Infarction (TIMI) Trial, Phase I: a comparison between intravenous tissue plasminogen activator and intravenous streptokinase: Clinical findings through hospital discharge, Circulation 76, No. 1, 142-154, 1987)

name: TIMI Flow Responses
definition: Partial perfusion. The contrast material passes across the obstruction and opacifies the coronary bed distal to the obstruction. However, the rate of entry of contrast material into the vessel distal to the obstruction or its rate of clearance from the distal bed (or both) is perceptibly slower than its entry into or clearance from comparable areas not perfused by the previously occluded vessel (e.g., the opposite coronary artery or the coronary bed proximal to the obstruction). (Chesebro JH, Knatterud GL, Roberts R, et al, Thrombolysis in Myocardial Infarction (TIMI) Trial, Phase I: a comparison between intravenous tissue plasminogen activator and intravenous streptokinase: Clinical findings through hospital discharge, Circulation 76, No. 1, 142-154, 1987)

name: TIMI Flow Responses
definition: Complete perfusion. Antegrade flow into the bed distal to the obstruction occurs as promptly as into the bed from the involved bed and is as rapid as clearance from an uninvolved bed in the same vessel or the opposite artery. (Chesebro JH, Knatterud GL, Roberts R, et al, Thrombolysis in Myocardial Infarction (TIMI) Trial, Phase I: a comparison between intravenous tissue plasminogen activator and intravenous streptokinase: Clinical findings through hospital discharge, Circulation 76, No. 1, 142-154, 1987)

name: Treatment Episode
definition: Having no previous example or precedent or parallel; of a kind not seen before.

name: Treatment Episode
definition: The repeated act of the dispensing, applying, or tendering of something to another after an initial treatment.

name: Treatment Failure Reason
definition: The mechanisms, functions, activities, or processes exhibited by microorganisms, especially bacteria, to resist or to become tolerant to antibiotics.

name: Treatment Failure Reason
definition: An indication that a medication schedule was modified by temporarily terminating a prescribed regimen of medication. (NCI)

name: Treatment Failure Reason
definition: Failure of a patient to follow medical advice, take medication as directed, or adhere to a prescribed course of treatment.

name: Treatment Failure Reason
definition: A drug serum concentration below therapeutic levels.

name: Trial Blinding Schema
definition: A study in which neither the subject nor the investigator nor the research team interacting with the subject or data during the trial knows what treatment a subject is receiving. (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Blinding Schema
definition: A trial in which subjects and investigators know which product each subject is receiving; opposite of a blinded or double-blind study. (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Blinding Schema
definition: A study in which one party, either the investigator or the subject, does not know which medication or placebo is administered to the subject; also called singlemasked study. (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Indication Type
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) aimed to cure a disease or condition. (NCI)

name: Trial Indication Type
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) aimed at identifying a disease or condition. (NCI)

name: Trial Indication Type
definition: A type of study designed to identify actions necessary to eliminate or reduce the risk to human life or well-being as a result of a particular medication or treatment regimen. (NCI)

name: Trial Indication Type
definition: A type of study designed to identify actions necessary to permanently eliminate or reduce the long-term risk to human life as a result of a particular medication or treatment regimen.

name: Trial Indication Type
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) for treatment of disease, syndrome or condition.

name: Trial Phase
definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context. (NCI)

name: Trial Phase
definition: The initial introduction of an investigational new drug into humans. Phase 1 studies are typically closely monitored and may be conducted in patients or normal volunteer subjects. NOTE: These studies are designed to determine the metabolism and pharmacologic actions of the drug in humans, the side effects associated with increasing doses, and, if possible, to gain early evidence on effectiveness. During Phase 1, sufficient information about the drug's pharmacokinetics and pharmacological effects should be obtained to permit the design of well-controlled, scientifically valid, Phase 2 studies. The total number of subjects and patients included in Phase I studies varies with the drug, but is generally in the range of 20 to 80. Phase 1 studies also include studies of drug metabolism, structure-activity relationships, and mechanism of action in humans, as well as studies in which investigational drugs are used as research tools to explore biological phenomena or disease processes. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8] (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Phase
definition: A class of clinical study that combines elements characteristic of traditional Phase I and Phase II trials. See also Phase I, Phase II.

name: Trial Phase
definition: Phase 2. Controlled clinical studies conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the drug for a particular indication or indications in patients with the disease or condition under study and to determine the common short-term side effects and risks associated with the drug. NOTE: Phase 2 studies are typically well controlled, closely monitored, and conducted in a relatively small number of patients, usually involving no more than several hundred subjects. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8] (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Phase
definition: A class of clinical study that combines elements characteristic of traditional Phase II and Phase III trials.

name: Trial Phase
definition: A clinical research protocol generally referred to as a pilot or feasibility trial that aims to prove the concept of the new intervention in question. (NCI)

name: Trial Phase
definition: A clinical research protocol generally referred to as a well-controlled and pivotal trial that aims to prove the mechanism of action of the new intervention in question. A pivotal study will generally be well-controlled, randomized, of adequate size, and whenever possible, double-blind. (NCI)

name: Trial Phase
definition: Phase 3. Studies are expanded controlled and uncontrolled trials. They are performed after preliminary evidence suggesting effectiveness of the drug has been obtained, and are intended to gather the additional information about effectiveness and safety that is needed to confirm efficacy and evaluate the overall benefit-risk relationship of the drug and to provide an adequate basis for physician labeling. NOTE: Phase 3 studies usually include from several hundred to several thousand subjects. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8] (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Phase
definition: A classification typically assigned retrospectively to a Phase III trial upon determination by regulatory authorities of a need for a Phase III B trial. (NCI)

name: Trial Phase
definition: A subcategory of Phase III trials done near the time of approval to elicit additional findings. NOTE: Dossier review may continue while associated Phase IIIB trials are conducted. These trials may be required as a condition of regulatory authority approval.

name: Trial Phase
definition: Phase 4. Postmarketing (Phase 4) studies to delineate additional information about the drug's risks, benefits, and optimal use that may be requested by regulatory authorities in conjunction with marketing approval. NOTE: These studies could include, but would not be limited to, studying different doses or schedules of administration than were used in Phase 2 studies, use of the drug in other patient populations or other stages of the disease, or use of the drug over a longer period of time. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8] (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Phase
definition: Postmarketing surveillance is sometimes referred to as Phase V.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Actual number of subjects enrolled; may include subjects who were not randomized.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicate if the study includes a prospectively planned opportunity for modification of one or more specified aspects of the study design and hypotheses based on analysis of data (usually interim data) from subjects in the study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The addition of a therapeutic product to the existing regimen in a clinical trial, where both entities remain as discrete products.
term: Test Product Added to Existing Treatment

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The anticipated maximum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The anticipated minimum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A therapeutically active agent that is intended to provide reference measurements for the experimental protocol of a clinical trial.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The protocol specified minimum amount of time needed to meet the definition of a confirmed response to treatment.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The literal identifier of the therapy or medication that is currently being given per protocol.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Text that describes the cutoff date.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A date which indicates any data collected by this date will be used for analysis.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The amount of drug administered to a patient or test subject at one time or the total quantity administered. [AMA Manual of Style] (CDISC Glossary)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The number of doses administered per a specific interval.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The unit of measure for the dosage form.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A standard from which a judgment concerning a medical diagnosis can be established.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicates whether assessors of ECGs for this study were blinded to subject identity, timing and treatment.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicates whether the 10-second ECGs for this study were extracted from a continuous recording.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The ECG lead which was planned to be used for ECG interval measurements for this study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicates whether all ECG interval measurements for the study were based on the same lead.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The degree of automation involved in assessing the ECGs for this study.
term: ECG Read Method Degree of Automation

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicates whether this study includes replicate ECGs for time points during the baseline portion of the study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicates whether this study includes replicate ECGs for time points during the on-treatment portion of the study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The algorithm used to identify the end of the T wave for ECGs for this study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The country name of planned study facility which has received IRB approval.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Indicate if persons who have not had the condition(s) being studied or otherwise related conditions or symptoms, as specified in the eligibility requirements, may participate in the study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The condition, disease or disorder that the clinical trial is intended to investigate or address.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The trial design developed to compare treatment groups.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The kind of product or procedure studied in a trial.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Planned length of observation for a single subject.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The planned number of intervention groups.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The principal purpose of the trial.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The auxiliary purpose of the trial.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Exploratory measures that will be used to evaluate the intervention(s) or, for observational studies, that are exploratory of the study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The primary measurement(s) or observation(s) used to measure the effect of experimental variables in a study, or for observational studies, to describe patterns of diseases or traits or associations with exposures, risk factors or treatment. These are the outcome measures used to assess the primary objective(s).

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Other key measures that will be used to evaluate the intervention(s) or, for observational studies, that are a focus of the study. These are the outcome measures used to assess the secondary objective(s).

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The pharmacological class of the investigational product.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
synonym: Anticipated Enrollment; Planned Enrollment; Planned Number of Subjects; Target Enrollment
definition: The planned number of subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The process of assigning trial subjects to treatment or control groups using an element of chance to determine the assignments in order to reduce bias. NOTE: Unequal randomization is used to allocate subjects into groups at a differential rate; for example, three subjects may be assigned to a treatment group for every one assigned to the control group. [ICH E6 1.48] See also balanced study. (CDISC glossary)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The randomization quotient is the number of planned subjects to be exposed to investigational therapy, independent of dose or other factors, divided by the total number of planned subjects.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Identification numbers assigned to the protocol by clinicaltrials.gov, EudraCT, or other registries.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A standard from which a judgment concerning a disease relapse can be established.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The course by which a substance was administered in order to reach the site of action in the body.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The protocol specified minimum amount of time needed to meet the definition of stable disease.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Final date on which data was collected for any subject (Date/Time of End of Participation, RFPENDTC) based on the protocol.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A standard from which a judgment concerning the severity of an event, disease or condition can be established.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The specific sex, either male, female, or mixed of the subject group being studied. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
synonym: Clinical Study Sponsor; Sponsor; Study Sponsor
definition: An entity that is responsible for the initiation, management, and/or financing of a clinical study.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The earliest date of informed consent among any subject (Date/Time of Informed Consent, RFICDTC) that enrolled in the study. For studies conducted without informed consent (ie. emergency use) use the date of treatment. Dates for subjects who were screen failures are not included.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The rule, regulation and/or condition that determines the point in time when a clinical trial will be terminated. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Selected pre-treatment factors by which patients are segregated to assure balance of these factors before randomization to the intervention arms of a clinical protocol.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Describes the role the study plays in determining the interventions a subject receives.

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of blinding for the trial. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: Comparator against which the study treatment is evaluated (e.g., concurrent (placebo, no treatment, dose-response, active), external (historical, published literature).

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: A grouping of individuals on the basis of a shared procedure or disease, or lack thereof (e.g. healthy volunteers, type 2 diabetic subjects, subjects with renal cell cancer). Standardized naming systems are available that define the groups within which a subject should be placed. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of trial, e.g. cure or prevention. (NCI)

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code

name: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code

name: Trial Type
definition: A study of the degree to which or rate at which a drug or other substance is absorbed or becomes available at the site of physiological activity after administration. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study most often used to compare the efficacy of different formulations to treat a given disease. It is the testing of an old versus a new formulation in healthy volunteers or subjects with the disease under study and usually in one dose. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study of the relative therapeutic efficacy of treatment of a disease. Usually this is a Phase II or III study. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: Studies that are conducted to assess the effect of food on the rate and extent of absorption of a drug, either compared to a fasted state or to a reference drug.

name: Trial Type
definition: A study that assesses an agent's ability to provoke an immune response.

name: Trial Type
definition: A study of the biochemical and physiological effect of a drug and the mechanism of drug action and the relationship between drug concentration and effect. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study that assesses the value associated with a given drug in therapeutic and economic terms. This type of study is multidisciplinary in nature and takes into consideration the social and economic costs (resource utilization costs including direct, indirect, and intangible costs) of drug therapy in addition to its direct therapeutic benefits. Analyses relate the difference in therapeutic benefits to the difference in costs between treatment alternatives. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study of identification and analysis of genomic variations that affect the efficacy of a drug. Pharmacogenomic studies can potentially be predictive of an individual's drug-response or adverse reactions or susceptibility to iatrogenic disorders, and may also reveal new targets that can help in the design of new drugs. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study of the process by which a drug is absorbed, distributed, metabolized, and eliminated by the body. (NCI)

name: Trial Type
definition: A study that assesses the medical risks to a subject. Safety is usually assessed by examining a wide range of clinical parameters, including adverse events, vital signs, physical exam, laboratory tests.

name: Trial Type
definition: A type of safety study that assesses the degree to which overt adverse effects can be tolerated by the subject.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: An assessment of the most clinically favorable overall response of the disease to the therapy.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: An assessment of the equivocality of disease progression based on a newly identified lesion.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: A non-radiological determination of disease progression based on symptoms or other findings.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: An assessment of the response of a non-target tumor(s) to the therapy.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: An assessment of the overall response of the disease to the therapy. (NCI)

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Code
definition: An assessment of the response of a target tumor(s) to the therapy.

name: Tumor Response Assessment Test Name
definition: An assessment of the response of a target tumor(s) to the therapy.

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: The disappearance of all signs of cancer in response to treatment. (NCI)

name: Tumor Response Result
synonym: Complete Remission with Incomplete Blood Count Recovery; Complete Response with Incomplete Bone Marrow Recovery
definition: The disappearance of all signs of cancer in response to treatment accompanied by incomplete bone marrow recovery, as evidenced by persistent anemia, thrombocytopenia or neutropenia.
term: Complete Response with Incomplete Bone Marrow Recovery

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Open to question.

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Unable to be evaluated. (NCI)

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Not all target tumors were assessed. Or not all non-target tumors were assessed.

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Persistence of one or more non-target lesion(s) and/or maintenance of tumor marker levels above the normal limits. (RECIST)

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: A disease process that is increasing in scope or severity. (NCI)

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: A finding indicating that there is a decrease in the size and the extent of tissue involvement by cancer.

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Cancer that is neither decreasing nor increasing in extent or severity based on predetermined boundaries. (NCI)

name: Tumor Response Result
definition: Remission with remaining lymphoid nodules reflecting residual disease.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: For neoplasms, a non-infiltrating and non-metastasizing neoplastic process that is characterized by the absence of morphologic features associated with malignancy (e.g., severe atypia, nuclear pleomorphism, tumor cell necrosis, and abnormal mitoses). For other conditions, a process that is mild in nature and not dangerous to health. (NCI)

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion, or site of disease that is present at baseline and will be quantifiably measured.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion, or site of disease which has not been previously seen or characterized.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion, or site of disease that is incapable of being measured at baseline.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion or site of disease that is present at baseline and not considered a target, but may be part of the objective assessment of the response to the therapeutic intervention.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion, or site of disease that is present at baseline and will not be quantifiably measured.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor, lesion, or site of disease that is present at baseline and is the target of the therapeutic intervention.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor or lesion that is present at baseline, located outside of or independent of any lymph nodes, and is the target of the therapeutic intervention.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a tumor or lesion located at or near the lymph node that is present at baseline and is the target of the therapeutic intervention.

name: Tumor and Lesion Identification Results
definition: The identification of a nodule that is the target of the therapeutic intervention.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The current value minus the lowest value previously recorded.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Absolute Change Nadir in Sum of Diam
definition: The current sum of diameters minus the lowest sum of diameters previously recorded.
term: Absolute Change From Nadir in Sum of Diameter

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The extent of a 2-dimensional surface enclosed within a boundary. (NCI)

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A semiquantitative analysis of the average uptake of analyte by body tissue in relation to the total administered dose of the analyte.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The length of a straight line passing through the center of a circle or sphere and connecting two points on the circumference. (NCI)

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The longest possible length of a straight line passing through the center of a circular or spheroid object that connects two points on the circumference.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether lesion failure occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether repeat revascularization of a lesion occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether a performed procedure of a target lesion is considered successful.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether limb failure occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The longest possible straight line or plane through a body or figure that is at a right angle to a given line or plane.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether clinical or functional ischemia is present before lesion revascularization occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether an appropriate clinical context was present before lesion revascularization occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The verification/confirmation by other methods or modalities that a tumor, which has not been previously seen or characterized, is present in the subject.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Baseline in Sum of Area
definition: The (current sum of areas minus the baseline sum of areas) divided by the baseline sum of areas, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Baseline in Sum of Area

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Baseline in Sum of Diam
definition: The (current sum of diameters minus the baseline sum of diameters) divided by the baseline sum of diameters, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Baseline in Sum of Diameter

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Baseline Sum Longest Diam
definition: The (current sum of longest diameters minus the baseline sum of longest diameters) divided by the baseline sum of longest diameters, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Baseline in Sum of Longest Diameter

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Baseline in Sum of Volume
definition: The (current sum of volumes minus the baseline sum of volumes) divided by the baseline sum of volumes, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Baseline in Sum of Volume

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The (current value minus the baseline value) divided by the baseline value, multiplied by 100.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The (current value minus the lowest value previously recorded) divided by the lowest value previously recorded, multiplied by 100.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Nadir in Sum of Diam
definition: The (current sum of diameters minus the lowest sum of diameters previously recorded) divided by the lowest sum of diameters previously recorded, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Nadir in Sum of Diameter

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Percent Change Nadir in Sum Longest Diam
definition: The (current sum of longest diameters minus the lowest sum of longest diameters previously recorded) divided by the lowest sum of longest diameters previously recorded, multiplied by 100.
term: Percent Change From Nadir in Sum of Longest Diameter

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The transparency of a material to the passage of X-rays and other forms of radiation.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The plane through a body or figure that is at the shortest width of that body or figure.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Sum of Area; Sum of Products of Perpendicular Diameters
definition: A calculation of the aggregated area values.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A calculation of the aggregated diameter values.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A calculation of the aggregated longest diameter values.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A calculation of the aggregated longest perpendicular values.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
synonym: Sum Diameters of Non Lymph Node Tumors
definition: A calculation of the aggregated diameter values for tumors other than the lymph nodes.
term: Sum of Diameters of Non Lymph Node Tumors

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A calculation of the aggregated diameter values taken from the viable portion of the tumor mass.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A calculation of the aggregated volume values.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: A condition or state of a tumor at a particular time.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The diameter of the portion of the tumor mass that is capable of growth, proliferation and metastasis.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: The amount of three dimensional space occupied by an object or the capacity of a space or container. (NCI)

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether vessel failure occurred.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether an artery is patent (free of TLR or restenosis) following intervention.

name: Tumor or Lesion Properties Test Code
definition: An indication as to whether repeat revascularization of an artery containing a lesion occurred.
